Cash is with the rescue One Dane At A Time. 
He was found as a stray with a broken (healed) neck, in Bakersfield. It appears his broken neck was never treated, had never affected his spinal cord and his mobility remained unaffected. The vet said there is nothing to be done and that this is not something she believes will ever affect him long term and that he should be able to continue to live the rest of his life as one big, goofy, happy boy!

Cash is a good, sweet, loving, affectionate yet STUBBORN boy. Cash is fully vaccinated, microchipped, neutered, crate trained and good with MOST dogs. 

Cash needs a STRONG, DANE EXPERIENCED leader that understands how obstinate he can be at times and act accordingly. Cash is located in Central California and is available for adoption NOW. If you're interested in Cash, please complete an adoption application on our website.

animal.description:
12/30/20: Nyla had a meet and greet last night with a family with another dog. We have determined that Nyla would probably do best in a home with no other pets as she has a very dominant personality and wants to lord over other dogs. Although she has done well with the dogs here, we feel that Nyla would just be happier getting all of the attention and not have to feel as though she needs to compete with another dog. We would also recommend an experienced dog owner and someone who is willing to set firm boundaries for Nyla. She is very smart and highly trainable but she also needs to know that she doesnt make the rules. Nyla has a lot of energy and is a strong dog, both physically and by sheer will. She needs a stronger owner that she sees as a leader. An active person who can get Nyla out and about or someone who can give her a job would be an ideal home for her.10/28/20: Nyla is heartworm positive. She has been started on ivermectin monthly so she will just need to be kept on the ivermectin each month until a negative test is obtained.
Nyla is a beautiful shepherd/spitz mix. She is approx 1 1/2-2 years old and currently weighs 64 pounds (she could stand to put on some weight and fill out more). Nyla has had a rough start in her young life. Nyla's original owners had a domestic situation which resulted in Nyla being left alone in a crate for a couple of weeks. She had no access to food or water and nearly died. A lady took her in and saved her life, however she had livestock and cats, both of which Nyla is not good with. After Nyla nearly killed her senior mini pony, she decided Nyla needed a different home that was more suited to her. Nyla can not go to a home with cats due to her high prey instinct. She seems to do fine with other dogs but would probably be best with dogs her size or larger or as an only pet. Nyla loves people and children. She walks fairly well on a leash (does pull alittle at times) and would make a good running, walking, hiking companion. Nyla loves to ride and will jump right in the car, ready to go. She would love a trip to the beach or a fun social day at the dog park. Nyla wants to be with you and does not like to be confined (understandable given her past). A fenced yard or leash walking would be needed for her and she would do best in a more active home. This girl has had it rough and its time for her to find the love, attention and care that she deserves and so desperately craves. Nyla's adoption fee will be $175 to help cover her vetting and cost of care. If interested in giving Nyla her forever home, please submit an adoption application (located on our homepage on petfinder) and your interest via email, text ONLY to 352-215-3260 (phone calls will not be answered or returned at this number), or FB message us.

No livestock of any kind
Dog selective, no cats

animal.description:
Max is a little over one year old lab mix. He knows most basic commands and then some.  He will stay, heel when walking, and wait for a command before he leaves his crate, goes outside, or eat that treat on the floor a couple of feet in front of him. He totally enjoys life and wants a new family who will enjoy it with him. He is great in the car and will walk right into the water, if you are into water sports.  

We think he would be great at dock diving. He is very athletic.  He needs a fenced yard with room to run.  Children running and playing with him would be a huge plus.  Max is the perfect family dog.  

Max will sometimes bark at other dogs until he gets to know them.  He is working on that and doing very well.  Until November, he lived most of his life on a farm with little interaction with other dogs.  His world has dramatically changed since he left the farm and he is enjoying it.  He loves people of all ages, especially children.  He considers himself one of them, which he is.  

Max is a healthy boy.  He is crate and leash trained.  He is up-to-date on vetting, neutered, and on heartworm prevention.  He is still growing and maturing.  He will probably end up around 65 lb.

For more information contact Judy at paxtonj@live.com or 865-300-8146. Adoption fee is $150.  Application online at www.almosthometn.org

animal.description:
Samson's stats:
Age: 10
Weight: 75lbs
Good with kids: I’m good with kids over 12 years old.
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats: Unsure
Fenced yard: Not required.
Suitable for townhouse and/or apartment: Yes
House trained: Yes.
Crate trained: I'm comfortable in my crate for short periods of time
Barks when left alone: No.
Chews inappropriate items: No
Training: I walk great on a leash, but I have no formal training.
Activity level: Laid back

Samson's fosterer writes...

Samson is loving his do-over life!

Two months ago, he was a sad sight …  every short, unsteady step seemed painful … open wounds on both ears from relentless fly-strikes … a tail that was hairless at its last 6 inches … and a coat that was caked with urine and feces.

Samson spent his life outside in a backyard pen, with his daily meal of leftovers usually the only contact with his owners. He was never taken on a walk. He didn’t pay much attention to people and when he did, he was pretty wary.

We worried that Samson might have given up on life … but you can’t keep a good dog down!

Every day since his arrival at his foster home has been another step on Samson’s journey to recovery. Every day, the medicines, supplements and good food have helped heal his body. The affection and constant company of his foster mom and dogs have gone a long way to heal his spirit.

Life outdoors exposed to the elements has made Samson super-appreciative of his new life indoors. He loves the comfort of a dog bed and house “training” came natural to him — he has never had a lapse! Samson’s started doing happy dog stuff like rolling around in the grass, chomping on his favorite toys and leaning in to his foster mom for head rubs.

He loves to chew; tree branches are a favorite outside, and indoors he channels the puppy in him by munching on Kongs and rubber toys, as well as hefty rope toys. He’s never happier though than when he’s quietly lying beside his foster mom, whatever she’s doing.

Samson loves other dogs but starts out a little over-excited with them. This usually passes quickly and he has become pals with his foster home’s little dog.

Samson sight and hearing are fine, and he only barks at stranger-danger. Since he does have arthritic hips, keeping his weight in check is important. At the moment he can climb stairs, though with some effort. Samson is receiving a number of medications and supplements that have greatly improved his mobility and comfort and he may well benefit from being on those for life. Short walks several times a day will also help keep Samson mobile, although he does love to stop and sniff as much as walk.

Samson has blossomed so much in just a few months! All he needs is a kind owner to live his happiest life.

If you can’t adopt Samson, but would like to support his ongoing care, please send donations to PGSPCA.org/donate and add a note that it’s for Samson.

Please consult our ADOPTION FAQ (http://www.pgspca.org/adopt/frequently-asked-questions/)  before contacting us.  If you are viewing this listing on a site that is not Petfinder or Adoptapet, please check our main site: 
http://www.pgspca.org/adopt/adoptable-animals-2
for the most up-to-date information on this pet.

If you are interested in Samson, consider letting us know by filling out a (no-obligation) adoption application (http://www.pgspca.org/adopt/online-adoption-application/) and we will arrange a meeting.
Due to his age and arthritis, Samson will not be attending adoption shows.

NOTE: We are an all-volunteer group and do not operate a shelter. All of our animals are in foster homes. Due to our requirement for a home visit, we generally only place animals within an hour's drive of Washington, DC. Questions can be directed to pgspca.adopt@gmail.com.

Like us on FACEBOOK!

animal.description:
Meet Hunter!

Get ready to fall in love with Hunter! That's me! I'm about 9 years old and 64 pounds. But don't let my age fool you, I'm a spunky boy with lots of love to give and will make a fun companion. Foster mom says that I'm sweet, silly, and social, and would thrive in a home where I can be close to my people and fur siblings. I'm a world class snuggler you should know. 
I'm completely house trained and crate trained and very willingly go to my crate, sometimes on my own! I enjoy freedom in the house (read: couch!) with supervision. I'm a curious, energetic guy who enjoys outdoor adventures and will keep you smiling and laughing everyday!
Lots of play and exercise help make me a good boy! I'm still learning important training basics, and would greatly benefit from continuing to work on my training with you. Positive reinforcement training with treats, did someone say treat?, is a great way to build my confidence and encourage me to do the right things, which I very, very much want to do! Oh, and I really love it when my foster mom kisses my face and tells me what a good boy I am! Maybe I'll find a new forever mom to do that too?! I really just need my people to give me guidance, direction, and structure.

I love all people, even children, but they say I may be a bit nich for younger kiddos. I can join a home with other dogs too! I currently live with two confident cats in my foster home who can handle my exuberance, though some supervision is still required. I have a lot of life in me, and get along with dogs of all sizes, male and female, who are sweet with me. Since I'm so excitable, I may do better in a home with a dog who is a little more calm and relaxed, but mainly I just need an experienced dog owner, not a first time dog owner. I'm sensitive to the energy around me, so a relaxed environment and family will help me stay calm and happy! I sure hope your home is the perfect one for me!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

Huck is a sweet 7-year-old, 50-pound Beagle-Hound mix on the trail for a scent to lead him to his forever home.

Huck has his nose guide his day, whether sniffing around the yard, or stopping to check his messages from other canines on walks. His favorite notes are the woodsy and floral smells wandering around the house or woods, or the fresh note of clean laundry or human musk that lets him know his people are around. After a long session of nose work, he will happily lay down to catch some rays and some zzzs in the sunshine.

Huck has been diagnosed with Glaucoma in both eyes. His left eye is totally blind but still has sight in his right eye. To help his right eye, he is taking daily drops. Huck does not let this stop him and simply goes about his day with little concern to what is happening to his eyes, and greets each person and new experience with a goofy grin.

Huck has done well with the additional spice of a canine friend in the home. He has not yet been around cats, so we are unsure of a feline pairing with him. While Huck hasn’t yet been around children, his sweet and laid back nature makes his foster thinks the fruity, silly nature of children could be a good top note in his forever home.

Huck is a sweet, easy-going pup looking for a family with a base note of love, a love note of kindness, and a top note of outdoor activity. Is your home the one to hit all the right notes for Huck?



His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
Mama Blue has come a long ways since being found abandoned, fighting to keep herself and her pups alive. She is about 4 years old & weighs about 30 lbs. Once she has had a stable, loving home she has thrived! Mama Blue is smart, gentle, and affectionate. At home, she loves to lounge around finding warm comfortable places to nap. Even better if a human is on the couch that she can snuggle with. Her calm demeanor along with her impeccable behavior make her an ideal dog to have around the house. Shes quiet, non-destructive, and accidents have been non-existent. Her current situation is just her and her foster but she spent a couple weeks in a home with other dogs, children, and a cat and she did great!

Her favorite part of the day is walks and would walk all day if she could! She loves the park and is fascinated by squirrels. Mama Blue is always friendly and calm when approached by other dogs she can be a little passive but usually warms up quickly and loves these small opportunities to interact with other dogs. Shes also a people and dog watcher. One of her favorite pastimes is to sit on top of the hill in the park and watch all the dogs and people playing!

Mama Blue is a fantastic companion that would be a great option for anyone looking for the calmness of an adult but the energy and enthusiasm of a puppy. This is an easy-going girl that would do well in nearly any situation as long as she is given love and attention!

animal.description:
TRUE DIAMOND IN THE ROUGH!

 

Tater Tot is just one of those dogs that begs to ask, "how did you get here?" It is apparent that this sweet girl must have been loved at the start of her young life. She is outgoing and social, has the beginning foundation of some great basic skills and then it is like her world just stopped...enter YOU!

Tater Tot is a bit of a Heinz 57; Labrador Retirever/Shepherd type mix with a wide and bright smile. She is approximately 1.5 years of age, weighs 60lbs, is up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative.

 

Tater tot is a recent graduate of the board and train program. She is pretty great at sit kennel and lie down. Her trainer notes indicate that she knows sit pretty but we are refining that skill still. Tater tot is treat driven, extremely smart and willing to be taught new things. The opportunities are endless with this sweet pup!

 

She is generally very well behaved in the house (she does not realize her size) and appears to be house trained. Tater Tot is very affectionate and loves to give hugs and kisses! She likes to be near her human, but is enjoys exploring the back yard and does not exhibit any type of anxiety in exporing her surroundings on her own. This smart gal loves to play with toys! Tater Tot will sleep in her crate all night without a peep and does not present any issues when asked to do so. She can even be caught napping in the crate from time to time.

 

Tater Tot is inquisitive even though she likes to be a part of the action, she already understands simple commands like no and down. She is very alert and attentive, so we think she will be easy to train! She appears to enjoy car rides (she jumped right into the car when we picked her up and has been well-behaved on the outings she has taken so far.

She will have small (adorable) outbursts of energy during the day when she gets excited and playful (zoomies) and she will need work to curb her remaining puppy tendencies to mouth (but is easily corrected). She also loves tossing around and playing with stuffed animals! Her leash manners are a work in progress, but make no mistake that this smart gal already knows that the presence of a leash, means she gets to go on a walk (and she gets very excited about that)! She will make a fantastic hike/walking partner in no time! 

Tater Tot will make an amazing family member! With some consistency and patience in her training, she will flourish as an amazing companion. She is so intelligent and eager to please. Her foster family has 3 kids (11-14) and she does extremely well with them. This girl has a great foundation and is looking for her forever home. Hopefully its you, you wont be sorry!

Please complete an application to meet Tater Tot today!

*Homeownership Required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
COLORADO BIO: 

Meet Heather! In the short time that we have had Heather, she has stolen our hearts. I can only imagine how loved she will be when she finds her forever home. Every foster family that has had the chance to meet Heather, has instantly fallen in love with her. Heather is slowly coming out of her shell as she soaks up all the love she can get from her foster humans. Now that her puppies have homes of their own, it is Heathers time to shine. Heather is kind, sweet, patient, and oh so gentle. She is amazing with people! Heather is sometimes a little slow to warm up, but she does excellent with a little patience and reassurance. 

Heathers favorite hobbies include car rides, long walks, cuddles, kisses, and anything to do with food. Heather loves cuddling up with a blanket in her kennel just as much as she loves cuddling up with her humans. She is very easy going! Heather does great in her kennel. She sleeps through the night in her kennel and she feels safe in her kennel when her humans are gone. On walks, she is easy on the leash, but she doesnt miss her shot at sniffing out a bunny.

Heather loves people and dog watching. She doesnt bark and just likes to observe. Heather is a little slow to trust other dogs. She does best with slow introductions to other dogs. After Heather has the chance to get to know another dog, she does much better at existing with that dog. 

Heather is learning how to play. She hasnt found her favorite toy just yet, but she loves bones and treats! We dont know how well she knows her commands, but she goes with the flow and follows her humans lead. She is very easily redirected and is a great listener. Heather is quick to catch on and has good manners. But if you leave a hot, juicy steak on the counter, she might just snatch it! 

Heathers golden eyes are so sweet and inviting. Her markings are beautiful and unique. She smacks her lips at the sound of food, and you know she is happy when her tail thumps away. Heather was focused on being a mama to her pups, but now she is ready for her own adventure! 

TEXAS BIO:

HEATHER'S TURN FOR A BEAUTIFUL LIFE...

Heather's past is not known outside of the fact that she and her young puppies were dumped at the door of a high-kill shelter in Houston, TX by "owners" whom would not be bothered long enough to even provide shelter staff her name. Immediately separated from her babies, Heather was left alone, praying that someone would come along to save her. Enter 2BABR to bring Heather AND her puppies to Colorado in hopes that each and every one of them will now have a fresh new beginning at the start of what we hope will be a wonderful life!

ENTER YOU: This beautiful girl has the most unique markings, certainly spurring conversation during your many walks to meet new people and take new adventures. Heather is suspected to be a Dalmation/Cattle Dog Mix; she is approximately 2 years of age, weighs just under 50lbs, is up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative. Heather was a wonderful mother to her babies and has initially tested well with other dogs.

*Homeownership Required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

Meet Kovu! Born 11/9/2012, Kovu is a gorgeous, sweet gentle giant weighing in at 82 pounds. He was surrendered to Chicago Animal Control when his owner could no longer care for him due to a condition called perianal fistulas, common in German Shepherd Dogs. With a good diet and medication, Kovu’s fistulas are well managed. He would benefit from a home where someone is home often to give him his daily meds. Kovu is currently fostered with a female GSD and lived previously with cats. Kovu especially likes to make friends with tiny dogs. As any typical GSD, Kovu gets attached to his humans. He loves to cuddle, walks well on leash, rides great in the car and has excellent house manners. Kovu is an all around fabulous boy that will make a lovely companion to a special home.

If interested in adopting Kovu, the first step is to complete an adoption application at www.gsrescue1.org

animal.description:
Have you met Pinky?

Little Pinky came to us from the Long Beach Shelter, where she was surrendered by her owners. She is approximately 13 years old and weighs 8 lbs. Pinky doesn't have teeth and enjoys soft food. Pinky is a sweet and quiet girl in our play yard, and she will jump into any available lap for pets.

It was a happy holiday season for Pinky! She got to go on TWO Flings - one for Thanksgiving and one for Christmas! This is very special because Pinky is in kidney failure so we really appreciate these families taking her to make her holidays shine! Here's what we've learned about her:

Pinky is a flirt and LOVES men and boys! Her very favorite person was her very own 10-year-old boy on her Thanksgiving Fling. She laid with him every chance she got and even got her crate moved to his room for bedtime so they could be close by. Pinky can be a picky eater but it was found that she really just prefers to graze over a period of time. She was fed in a separate room to give her space from the other family dog and would bark when she was finished and wanted to rejoin the family. Pinky lived with other small dogs in both of her Fling homes. She co-exists with other dogs just fine, but doesn't really interact with them. Because of her kidney issues, Pinky has to potty frequently. Both of her Flingers found that Pinky does seem to know to go potty outside and if you take her out when she gets up from her naps she will potty right away! One family tried potty pads at night and she seemed to know to use them as well.

One of her Flingers shared, "This weather is a bit too chilly for Miss Pinky, but she has found her favorite spot on our couch and I wrapped her in a throw. She loves my 10 year old son and is always looking for him. She ate THREE huge meals yesterday and kept asking for more. She is a big fan of The Honest Kitchen dehydrated food. She loves her cozy round bed in her crate and happily "makes her bed." She goes to bed at 7pm and easily sleeps 12 hours in her crate. She really just needs a calm home with a warm bed, a warm sweater, and your warm heart."

Pinky is currently living in a Foster home, but she would love a Forever Family.

Pinky is considered hospice. We will gladly cover her lifelong medical care and teach you how to care for a kidney dog if you have a little extra love to spare. Apply at:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/24/21 KG

animal.description:
Hermes joined our rescue on October 27th from Georgia in search of his new forever home.  This poor guy has been through a lot in the last year :-(.  His owner had passed away and he had a life long friend named Gizmo.  When his owner passed, he was taken in by a family who had dogs, cats and kids.  Life was good for about 9 months, but then all the dogs started squabbling; the husband and wife got a divorce and Hermes and Gizmo found themselves living on a screened in porch for 3 months.  As you can figure the story.....they ended up at the shelter.  Gizmo and Hermes were separated and now trying to figure out life by themselves in new and scary places :-(.

Hermes is nervous when meeting new people.  He can give a bark and even growl, but he does warm up once he knows you.  We are letting him settle in at his own pace.  Hermes loves to go for walks and has this cute prance/trot while walking :-).  He is house trained and seems to just be a couch potato....as most senior dogs can be.  He is pretty quiet and has only barked when the house dog did...LOL!  His foster home has an older, smaller dog that he has been completely fine with.

We feel since Hermes is nervous in meeting new people, no children in the house.  The most ideal home for this senior boy is a quiet one with not a lot of "traffic".  He really just wants to chill out and relax without a lot of chaos!  Who can blame him!!

Hermes is 10 years old and appears to be a Jack Russell Terrier mix weighing in at 20 lbs.  We have had him to the vet and did his bloodwork, urinalysis and fecal tests.  He is current on vaccines, neutered, and current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention.  His adoption fee is $250.

If you are interested in Hermes, please submit an application on our website at https://worthytails.rescuegroups.org.  For any questions you have, please send an email to jessie.wilson@comcast.net.

Thank you for your interest in a senior, rescue dog!!

animal.description:
Cohen is an adorable, affectionate, Pittie/Lab mix who is 3 years old and weighs 57 lbs.  He is a sweet, gentle, easy going, boy who was a staff favorite at the Walker County shelter where he was picked up as a stray.  He is a happy, friendly, sometimes timid boy who would do well in just about any household.  He craves human interaction so he's looking for a person/family where he can spend time with his people during the day.  He is a playful, medium energy boy who needs a tall fence in his yard because if his person steps onto the other side of the fence where he can see them, he may try to jump the fence to be with them.  Cohen gets along with kids & other dogs, but needs slow introductions, and is afraid of cats (he walks away from the cat in his foster home when he sees her).  When meeting new dogs he typically limits his actions to mutual sniffing & is otherwise disinterested.  He would do well with other dog who doesn't repeatedly try to engage him.  He has good leash manners (pulls occasionally, but responds to correction), knows basic commands (crate & sit), and loves car rides.  He is a handsome boy with the cutest jowls ever and he'll be a loyal, devoted companion for the lucky person/family that adopts him!

Cohen is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  He was HW+ when he came to BarkVille but has completed his treatment and is now healthy & ready to find his loving, forever home!

For more information about Cohen, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt sweet Cohen, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Athena is an incredible girl! Looking for a dog who loves people? Look no further! Looking for a dog who is fun-loving, athletic, and a joy to be around? Athena is more than qualified! 

Athena is an American Bulldog, and she is some kind of wonderful! She was found as a stray and was thin. She was very stressed at the shelter, and she really needed to get out of the shelter environment. We asked to take her so she could recover. 

Athena is a big and strong girl, currently weighing about 85-90 pounds.  She is very athletic and active, and loves playing with her toys! However, she loves snuggling with her humans and really longs to be a part of a family. She gives the best kisses, and just loves to love and cuddle. 

Athena initially was very reactive to other dogs, but she has improved SO MUCH! There are some dogs here that she likes to lay beside on either side of the fence. She has a best friend at the rescue, and they will be walked together as weather allows. 

Athena requires a fenced yard with a 6 foot privacy fence. She needs the opportunity for supervised play so she can remain healthy (physically and mentally). She needs continued work with manners, but she has improved by leaps and bounds!  She does well with kids, but they should be at least 8 or 10 years old or older, only because she doesn’t realize how big she is and she can knock over younger ones by accident. 

We would love for Athena to find her family so she can cuddle and play as much as she wants.  We would need her new family to live within about an hour of Greenwood Indiana.

NOTE: If you are interested in adopting Athena, please reply with your email, or email us directly at Heartbeat4paws@gmail.com and we will send you an application.  Also, please note that an in-person home visit is required prior to adoption, and cannot be waived. We will gladly take appropriate precautions as needed for the safety and comfort of all.

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  DO NOT USE the e-mail attached to this account. Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

ARTHUR is available for adoption! However, only to a family/home that can properly confine him which means either in their home or in a securely fenced yard. He is listed as a lab/bulldog mix and he is black in color with white on his chest. He is estimated to be four years old and he weighed 75 pounds at his intake in late August.  ARTHUR arrived at the shelter after reportedly killing a small dog. He had been running loose at the time and it was not the first time he had been picked up. So, he also cannot go to a home that has small dogs. The alleged attack has not been verified as nobody filed a report with animal control to document it. Staff has no way of knowing how he would be around any other dogs or cats. Staff says that he is a very happy dog and a sweet one, too. You can schedule an adoption appointment to meet him. Or, you can just call staff for any other observations they may have about his behavior at the shelter during his time there. A big thank you to the staff member who agreed, and was able, to get him outside for some decent photos while we still have sunlight. His shiny, pretty coat and his big smile show much better outside than they would from a photo taken inside the shelter. ARTHUR is a pretty dog and people friendly. He has not yet been neutered. So, please read the important information below.

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

You'd be hard-pressed to find a cuter guy than Humphrey, a 5 year-old Pug/Terrier mix male who came to Canine Lifeline from an overcrowded rural county dog shelter. We don't know how Humphrey came to be in the shelter but he was happy to make the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could enjoy life in a foster home while searching for a permanent new home. This little guy was adopted from us in Oct 2020 but recently returned because he proved to be too energetic and dominant for the other little dog in the home. Humphrey does like to have things his way so needs a dog-experienced owner (preferably a single woman) who is able to manage him properly and set him up for success. Humphrey is crate-trained and likely to be housetrained too although we can't guarantee that he won't have accidents in his new home as he gets used to his new routine. He enjoys going out for a walk and does quite well on a leash. While he becomes very attached to his people, Humphrey can be nervous when meeting new people so needs a quiet home without many visitors. If there's another dog in the home, it will need to be one who can handle rough play but who is also able to live with Humphrey's desire to be in charge. He's a short and stocky little guy who definitely likes his snacks so will need a home where he will get lots of walks around the block in combination with moderate snacking so that he doesn't get too chubby. Humphrey weighs about 21 pounds and his adoption fee is $375. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. Since coming to us, Humphrey has had a dental cleaning and now flashes a pearly white smile. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Humphrey. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Humphrey and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Allow us to introduce Bodhi and share his survival story!

10-year-old Bodhi was found trapped in a small canal at a Tijuana park. His rescuer reached out to us and asked if we could help Bodhi get medical care and find a forever family. She believed Bodhi had been used as a bait dog and then discarded in the canal where he was found. Bodhi arrived at Frosted Faces on October 23rd with gaping wounds, so skinny you could see every rib, and jaundice to the point his gums were more yellow than pink. His recovery has been miraculous and he hardly looks like the same dog anymore!

Bodhi became a quick favorite of our volunteer physical therapist who donates her time and skills to help some of our worst off Frosted Faces. She spent a lot of time with Bodhi doing laser therapy on his wounds. She shared, "Bodhi exemplifies all of what is so special about dogs. He is most forgiving and loving. The condition he arrived in was heart wrenching. Bodhi was a willing and accepting recipient to all of the care he received and continues to receive. I feel fortunate to be apart of his wound and heart healing. He allowed me to provide manual therapy, laser therapy, and wound care. His profound improvement has been remarkable, especially in a relatively short period of time. Bodhi's incredible spirit and willingness to overcome what appears to have been something awful, serves as a role model for anyone going thru something really tough."

As Bodhi's recovery progressed, he began going on walks and then hikes with volunteers. They report he enjoys walking, sniffing, and taking breaks for treats and pets. Bodhi hangs out with other Frosted Faces in our play yards and gets along well with them. He loves to be petted by everyone he meets and get belly rubs, too! Bodhi is a sweet and gentle boy who has earned the privilege of being one of our lobby dogs. It is so fun to see Bodhi full of life and acting like a house dog! He sits on the couch and does wrestle mania in the yard! He begs for food, and helps "scoop dinners" by sticking his whole head in the feeding tub and stealing kibbles.

On January 28th, Bodhi had FHO surgery. A femoral head osteotomy is the removal of the "ball" part of the ball-and-socket that makes up the hip joint. This way, the bones of the joint are no longer in contact, which eliminates the pain that is caused by the abnormal contact of the bones in a dog with hip dysplasia or severe osteoarthritis. Bodhi came through surgery really well and was out enjoying walks with his Frosted Friends the next day!

Bodhi is available for adoption, but we would like to keep him local to the San Diego area for his medical appointments. We will cover his care for the rest of his life.

Stop by and meet magicial and miraculous Bodhi at our next Open House!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
A SWEET, SMART GAL:  10 years old / 50 lbs. 

Hi there!  My name is Bernice!  I was at animal control uncomfortable with yucky skin issues, hair loss and infected ear – ouch!  Thankfully Mostly Mutts came to rescue me and quickly started addressing my needs.  I am now feeling good and am ready to find a furever family to love!    

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I’m looking for a home without other dogs as I have not liked the one’s I met at MM’s / Cats unknown / I’m looking for a home with no kids please. I met two children at Mostly Mutts (ages 7 and 11), and I did NOT like it when they ran around near me, and I showed a little aggression over it.   

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a friendly girl with an absolutely adorable nature.  The volunteers say I’m sweet, social and charming.  Though I am an older girl, you would never know it when you see my playful side / My energy level is pretty high at 6-8, so I do like activity.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I'm a proud graduate of the Mostly Mutts University training program, so, I’ve mastered the ‘sit’, ‘stay’, ‘down’, ‘come’, ‘drop it’, ‘leave it’ and ‘place’ commands.  I also use proper door etiquette and have good leash manners as well as accept nice strangers without jumping.  What a smart girl I am! / My crate manners are good at Mostly Mutts / I also have good potty habits on the shelter schedule, so hopefully that will be the case in my new home too.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I LOVE people and enjoy the company of the volunteers who care for me at the shelter – especially when they take me to the play yard for my favorite activity – fetching balls! I love all kinds of doggie toys and really enjoy my training sessions, since I am a fan of treats and I like to learn. I also like to chase squirrels and chipmunks – he he / I can’t think of any dislikes, but I would not be happy if I did not get the love, care and attention all dogs deserve!  

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.  

I am looking for a fun family to enjoy life with!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

Hi, my name is Willow. I'm looking for a family that will adopt me and keep me until I leave this world. 
A good samaritan found me in a ditch with just a blanket. I was hurting, covered in demodex mange and had hookworms. I thought my time was up, but once I was found, they got Just Cause rescue to take me in and get me well. My foster mom loves me, and gave me a warm bed to sleep in, and some good food. She says she can't keep me, but will find me a good home, where I'll be loved. I hope shes right. I get on with other dogs, not sure about cats, cause there's none at my foster moms house. I'm still a little clumsy around the small dogs, but I do give them lots of kisses, even when they don't want them. All my fur has now grown back, and I have a beautiful brindle colored coat. Short hair, and haven't shed in my mom's house.
I'm about 9 months old, up to date on all my vaccinations,  and spayed. I weigh 35lbs.
Please will you consider taking me in. I am kennel trained and potty trained, and working on my leash training now. Hope to see you soon, I'm ready to give you some kisses xx.

animal.description:
No Phone Calls -Please fill out an adoption application and send it back to us to be approved. No Elderly Owners and No Out of State Adoptions due to this dogs past in case it doesn't work out. He will do best with an owner 50 years old or younger. He is working with a trainer until we can get him adopted.  He is an active dog and cannot live in any home with a senior owner. Absolutely no children or grandkids. 

Hi There,

My name is Jo Jo. I am a very active, handsome 4 year old black n white Cavalier-Sussex Spaniel mix or could be some Basset in me. I was bought from a breeder who passed me off as an English Cocker.  Not sure just why, but my owner dropped me off at a NC shelter where I was alone and scared. A rescue group took me into their care where I had several foster homes. Then I was flown across NC to another place. This was scary and stressful. I bit three people while being handled. This rescue group didn't know quite how to deal with my behavior issue so they looked into help from another rescue willing to work with me. Transport was arranged and I did pretty well on the initial meet n greet. Every day I've been here these folks are working with me, challenging me, correcting me and teaching me how to behave like a good dog should. 

I am heartworm negative, current on shots and I have been neutered. I need an adult only home with a good alpha owner willing to work with me, not give up on me and can truly give me a 2nd chance in a home with a good life.  The best environment for me is a calm home with very few distractions, no children, no grand children and no senior owners.

My adoption fee is $350.
animal.name: Jo Jo -Needs Experienced Adult owner, No Children, No Grandkids

animal.description:
Hi, everyone! I've been in my foster home for 3 months now, and have been making great progress. I'm much better at pottying outside, but am primarily pad trained. While I'm still afraid of humans, I've decided that my foster parents aren't so bad. They still have to catch me in order to pet and snuggle me, but I now settle right in and fall asleep on the couch with all my other fur siblings. I also don't run away from mom and dad as quickly or as far as I used to, and I return to them much faster.

I've found my voice and bark when I know it's dinner time, or when I decide mom and dad have something delicious that I'd like to try. I come right up to them for treats, too. I try to play with my foster brother and sisters, but they're older than I am and sometimes aren't interested. I still require a fenced yard, and it would be great if I could find a home with another dog to be my buddy.A home with no kids would be best, or a home with children older than 12 if there are kids.

While I still don't care for a leash, my mom has put a harness on me a couple of times and I do better with the harness. I'm still not ready for walks, but I'm making some progress. Baby steps! 

I'm being fostered in Antioch, IL and my adoption fee is $350. If you're interested in applying to adopt me, please contact Anna, my foster mom, at 847.757.1748 or annabaker2011@gmail.com.

animal.description: Meet Benson! This handsome boy is about 3.5 years old and 70 lbs of love! Benson loves nothing more than to feel safe and snuggle on the couch or lounge around with his humans. He is very sweet and gives a lot of love! Benson is great with humans (kids 10+ ok too) and loves to meet new people. He’s very smart and quick to learn new tricks like high five, paw, stay, sit and lay. He’s also crate and potty trained! Benson was not properly trained or introduced to other animals early on in his life, so he has a high prey drive. We are working with a trainer in Eugene, OR who is helping him appropriately react to other animals. However, due to his reactivity, he will need a home where he is the only pet and has a very secure (6ft +) and solid fenced yard (no chain link or other see through fences). Benson has learned a communication system built on rewards and positive verbal markers. This system can be used to continue to develop and nurture his self confidence. Much of his dog reactivity is rooted in a lack of feeling safe. To thrive he will need a strong leader to advocate for him, manage his occasional outbursts of leash reactivity (towards cats/dogs) and to protect him from harm. His ideal match is someone mentally alert enough and physically strong enough to correct and redirect him when he fails to control his impulses. He enjoys affection and praise which can be used as a form of reward. Due to Benson's strength and size, a muzzle should always be worn when out in public. He does have mild separation anxiety and is more comfortable when his human is with him. He is crate trained which can be used at times when he must be left alone. He has shown no signs of human aggression or resource guarding but he seems to have had previous success grabbing the leash away from his handler when overstimulated or frustrated. Another reason a muzzle is ideal for leash walking or being on leash in public. Benson needs a family or best friend who can manage his size and strength, and is ok with him staying at home or playing in the yard (and being managed appropriately). He is not for someone looking for a running or walking partner, or someone that wants to take their dog out to the breweries. He is a sweet human bonded dog that wants to be by your side at home, and will reward you with lots of snuggles and kisses. Benson's trainer has graciously offered to help any potential adopter with transitioning Benson into his new home and provide support. Benson has had a tremendously difficult life but he is ready to find love and support in a family who loves him. Benson was rescued from a shelter in Los Angeles, CA and is being fostered in Eugene, OR. Will you be his hero?

animal.description:
Please welcome Foster Elmer!  This little nugget (weighing in at just 14lbs) is the sweetest! He loves to be held and snuggled, and is quite a talker when he has something to say (like being put down! Lol). He’s getting along well with our other pugs and is quite social.

Elmer was rescued from a shelter and we know very little about his past, other than it was rough. His age is estimated to be 11-ish.  Unfortunately, this little guy has a laundry list of issues that we will be addressing:
1. heartworm+
2. ehrlichia (blood condition)
3. ear infection
4. conjunctivitis and dry eye
5. yeasty skin
6. severe hip dysplasia that may require surgery (Rimadyl for now)

Elmer will eventually go through heartworm treatment. In the meantime, his eyes and ears are getting treated, he’s on an antibiotic for the ehrlichia, and he’ll be getting baths with Pharmaseb medicated shampoo twice a week for his skin. He’s a skinny little guy that we are trying to fatten up. And he has scrawny little chicken legs with a wonky gate. It doesn’t seem to slow him down much, but we hope he’ll get stronger with time.

Foster Elmer won’t be ready to adopt for some time, but keep following his journey, and please consider making a donation to PugHearts toward his care.

animal.description: If you are looking for a dog that supplies endless hugs, Birch is your man. He is such a sweetheart with a yearning to be your 60-pound lapdog. In a couple of ways, Birch can be slightly mischievous. He can jump with ease, so a four-foot fence would not likely stop him from flying over. He can be a bit of a rough-and-tumble player with other dogs, so any other dogs in the home would need to be tolerant of that. Birch has been with us since early October, and the shelter environment has been stressful for him. A patient, loving home with plenty of couch space for naps would likely take all of his anxieties away!

animal.description:
**This dog is with Corridor Rescue in Houston, Texas**

Dudley was rescued in September, along with his buddy Boomer. Knowing he had a limp when we rescued him, we knew we could be looking at fairly large vet bills. BUT, we're not in rescue to save money, we're in rescue to save dogs. 
However, Dudley is one of the very rare cases where things turn out to be better than they appear! After observing this bundle of joy who is so happy to be alive, it has been determined that since he's using his leg normally and does not appear to be in any pain, his leg stays! If, in the future, he looks to be in pain or quits using his leg, amputation is the only option as it is a completely healed fracture. 
So, Dudley remains a 4-legged, happy-go-lucky, goofy boy. And he's looking for his forever home!

***
Please apply to foster or adopt online at www.corridorrescue.org

Direct inquiries to: adopt@corridorrescue.org

The adoption fee of $225 covers spay/neuter, microchip and current vaccines.

Transport is available and can be discussed on an individual basis.

Thank you for considering a rescued former street dog for your next family member!

animal.description:
Meet Jersey! Jersey was a known "stray", wandering the streets of a small South Georgia town for months before being taken in my a Good Samaritan. Before that, she had lived her life on a chain. When her "owners" were located and contacted, they had no interest in taking her back or giving her the loved life she so deserves, so her Good Samaritan Guardian Angel kept her safe until rescue could be secured. 
 

Jersey came to RMG just one day before giving birth! She was a great mom to all of her pups but now she has declared that her Mom days are over and she is ready to be spoiled and pampered herself! Jersey is good with other dogs and absolutely LOVES people!
 

Sadly, just like about one in three dogs we rescue Jersey is heartworm positive. RMG utilizes a slow kill method of treatment developed at UGA that does not require any exercise restrictions or changes to daily life. All treatment related medications are provided and there are typically no lasting health effects after successful treatment. 

Interested in adopting this sweet princess and showing her what life is like as a beloved family member? Email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

To learn more about him, send us an email at adoptycas@gmail.com

animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Collin
Size: ~Large range: 61-100 lbs
Adoption Donation:$250 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Neutered Male, Vaccinations current, Microchip, Older considerate children only, NOT Apartment-friendly

Collinwill be extremely happy to have a forever home.

Foster Home Feedback

*
NOT Apartment-friendly

*
Older considerate children only

1/10/21: Collin has been in my home a little over a month now, and he has been loving getting spoiled!! He came into my home because his former foster thought he would thrive in a home with younger dogs to play with. Over Christmas, my three grandkids ages 4, 5, and 9, and their 5 Chihuahuas spent the week visiting, and he did very well with all of them. He had so much fun playing with the grandkids and the 5 Chi's that when we dropped him off at his former fosters on Christmas Eve, for the night, he slept for 15 hours straight.

He loves to snuggle and knows no personal spaces; Collin will take over the entire bed or couch if you let him. He loves to be outdoors, once he goes out it is hard to get him back inside. He likes to go out and sit on the deck or in the middle of the yard and scan for rabbits, he does not care if it is snowing or sleeting or if it is day or night.

Collin is a very typical young pup, he is just a great big oaf and a blockhead, who thinks everything is a toy. When he first got here, he and I had to have a few conversations and redirections on why my shoes were not his toys, since then he has been fairly good about that. He is also a huge goofball, and good for some laughs because he is big and clumsy.

Overall, Collin is just a big, loveable goofball that just wants a forever home where he can snuggle on the couch with his forever person or people, hog the bed at night, protect them from the big bad rabbits in the backyard and smother them in love and kisses.

With some training and lots of snuggling, this boy will be a great companion for some lucky forever home.

11/23/2020: Collin is loving the home life! I've been taking Collin to a basic manners class at Down Dog Studio, and he is a model student. He is learning so quickly and is super treat-motivated.

Collin would thrive in a house with a dog playmate who can match his energy. He loves to run and loves to wrestle. I have a 10lb Chihuahua with no teeth who loves to instigate fights with Collin, which Collin perceives as playtime! While my Chi is trying to inflict damage with his gums, Collin is gentle enough (dumb enough?) to play and not actually hurt my idiot dog.

Collin does great on walks. He doesn't pull much, especially with the use of an EZ Walk harness. We are working through some car reactivity, but again, he is super treat-motivated, and it will be easy to redirect this behavior.
Collin loves car rides! He jumps in, sits down, and hardly makes a peep.

Collin is great with both people and dogs. This weekend, he met three young kids ON bikes, and only gave kisses! No bike reactivity, no kid reactivity, no stranger danger. I do think Collin would need only older kids in his house as he is high energy and could knock some little ones over easily.

Once Collin gets settled down, he is a giant snuggle bug. He loves to cuddle. He is absolutely a bed hog, but is the cuddliest goofball you'll ever meet!
To sum up, Collin is an oversized puppy. He has a ton of energy that he needs a dog playmate to help work out, and a house that can offer him both physical and mental exercise and stimulation. He is super smart and will train easily! Collin will be an amazing companion and is looking for the right house to jump into.

10/7/2020: Collin is doing great in his foster home. He is learning that his kennel means a Sunbutter Kong and a handful of treats! He is slowly learning "sit," "gentle," and "leave it." Collin is still very energetic and will need someone who can provide a lot of both mental and physical activity/exercise. Collin is still a young dude and has a lot of energy that he doesn't know how to express. We're trying to learn how to greet guests at the door, as right now, he is very jumpy and mouthy.

Collin is a very sweet boy who just wants someone to play with. He is dog friendly and loves people (no stranger danger with this guy). He walks great on an EZ Walk harness, with minimal pulling when he sees local wildlife. Collin's prey drive is very strong and he loves to chase. So we are also working with impulse control. Collin is going to need someone who is willing to work with him. I think Collin is going to be a really great companion for someone who realizes and can work with his potential!

9/15/2020: Colin! Colin is a rambunctious and playful guy! He is lacking in some basic manners, but we are working on it. He is a very typical young Lab (mix) with lots of energy, and the propensity to find anything as a toy. He does well with redirecting. Colin is pretty quiet inside, but does bark a lot outside, especially at urban wildlife. We have some neighbor squirrels who love to tease the dogs and drive them bonkers. He seems to love everyone and other dogs. On walks, Colin does fairly well but is showing some reactivity to cars. Again, he redirects very easily and feeds off positive praise.

I have been crating Colin while I am out, and he does not like it. I have been working on this as well with him. He has escaped from a wire kennel, and will require a more closed kennel to contain him. At night, he sleeps so soundly on my bed with me and my resident dogs. He looooooves to snuggle and will snore in your ear all night. I don't think he slept on a soft bed until he came into rescue.

I would not recommend a house with young children, as Colin is still very full of energy and is in his jumpy and mouthy phase of young dog age. He would do well with someone who can devote time into training him and give him some good exercise to burn off his energy.

Colin is a very sweet boy who is learning that home life is a great life. Please consider this happy boy for your companion!

9/7/2020: Colin has awesome leash manners; no pulling and just a great walker. Colin is treat-motivated and also likes to give hugs! To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
Norah is a sweet unassuming personality who seems to get along well with any dog she meets. Not very self-assured, she'll let most dogs be alpha to her subordinate nature. When you meet her you'll notice her beautiful eyes. They are somewhat crossed but she doesn't seem to notice. She was seem by a vet specialist who said her eyes are completely healthy and that she was likely born this way.

She's already crate trained and does not mess in her crate, waiting patiently for her turn outside. Norah will make a loving companion to someone willing to give her time to trust them....which only takes a little food frankly.

Norah was found wandering on a country road with two puppies from her last litter who were probably the lone survivors. When you're born in a field you're easy prey for predators when mom goes searching for food. Another rescue stepped up for the puppies but didn't want "the mom, so we were glad to give Norah a soft place to land. She's already crate trained and does not mess in her crate, waiting patiently for her turn outside. Norah will make a loving companion to someone willing to give her time to trust them....which only takes a little food frankly.

animal.description:
Hi there, I'm Coco! I'm a very sweet and affectionate girl, with lots of energy and love to give. I came to Rescue Village after spending several months at another shelter. Coco will do best in a home without small/young children and she prefers to be the only furry companion in the home.

A word from Coco's foster family: She is housebroken and has not chewed on anything that is not hers. She is really a very loving dog. No barking or whining. Well, she will bark a little in the car when we are going for a walk, just a bit, not constant. She plays and prances with her toys, then she settles down for awhile. We are able to get her out for walks a lot, several times a
day, and I think that helps control the energy. 

Like most of us, she doesn't care to get wet when it's raining, and she seems content to settle down and relax when it's raining and does not beg to go out. She will be a great, loving dog for someone who can give her enough exercise, either walking or a fenced yard.

animal.description:
Hi!

My name is Tippy, glad to see you here on my page!

I'm some sort of Lab mix, but that just makes me more pretty and special don't ya think?  :)

I was found with my 5 siblings when were only 10 months old in a single axle horse trailer on July 3. Our owners had not even bothered to clean it out when they put us in there.  There was manure and other poop at least 8 inches deep.  It was horribly nasty in there. Attached to this trailer was a small, makeshift pen that was filled with poop, water and dare I say, maggots!  It was the worst situation any living being could be left in.  Some people are just so cruel, I just don't get it!

The great peeps at Lucies raced in early on the morning of July 4.  A newspaper article was written about the rescue and we were donned the name '"The Freedom Six Pack".

I can't remember how long we suffered being in those awful conditions.  As soon as we were rescued and brought to Lucies, we each got to feel grass for the first time in our young lives.  It was the most amazing feeling ever!  The ladies that brought me teared up at our response to the grass, because it was both sad and amazing at the same time.

One of my brothers was missing a toe because of those filthy conditions.  For the first 2 weeks we were at Lucies, we all slept standing up in a pyramid style, as we had never known clean and dry conditions. 

I'm so glad we are here now and are doing so much better. These volunteers here really know how to love and take care of us.

I can be shy at times, but believe it or not, I am extremely outgoing and I love to play.  I especially LOVE being in the water and splashing around!  I am K9 friendly and I am also leash and crate trained.

While it's really awesome here, I would truly love to have a family of my own to play and cuddle with.  I sure hope that's you!  Thanks for visiting my page.  Hope to see you soon!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Winnie came to us as a stray from Hillsborough County Animal Services three years ago. She was adopted but the situation in that home changed as life happens and Winnie came back to us.   At 8 years old this sweet girl had eye issues which we took care of surgically and now just requires drops daily, she's a food lover so she's on a special low calorie diet and her arthritis is maintained easily by daily supplements.  Winnie is around 65lbs, 8 years old, and dog friendly. She enjoys the company of her humans and just wants to be in your lap! 
Winnie is in a foster home in the Tampa, Florida area and is ready for adoption! Interested in meeting her? Fill out an application on our website www.newlifedogrescue.com
ATTENTION:
Please note, all of our dogs are in foster homes. You must fill out a application before you can meet/see the dogs we have available. 
If you see the dog on here, it is still available. If curious on updates of a dog, check out our facebook page! 
https://www.facebook.com/newlifedogrescue/


Adoption Process:
Fill out an application at www.newlifedogrescue.com
We will do a background check and verify home ownership. If rental, we must receive a letter from the
management company or owner on their letter head approving the breed listed of the dog they are
inquiring about. If the background check has any discrepancies or the current animals in the home are
not current on vaccinations we will void the application.
We do a home inspection. Often times we will do a meet and greet in the home with the dog and the
family if they are in the Tampa Bay area and have another animal in the home.
If all is approved then the adopters will complete a final contract form and the donation is made at
which time the health records and all shot records are turned over to the new owner.

animal.description:
Roxy is a loving, senior, girl despite living a lonely eight years tied to a backyard chain. She was used to breed puppies, which may be why she doesn't like other dogs. She is very affectionate towards people and greets everyone she knows with excitement. Roxy has worked with a trainer and a consistent foster parent so she knows basic commands and has come a long way with her manners. She loves to be with humans and take a snooze next to you while you work. She loves walks and laying in sunny spots. She goes in her crate when her foster mom leaves and does well. She is potty trained, spayed, microchipped and up to date on all of her vaccinations. She's been great with teenagers but Roxy hasn't had an opportunity to be around younger children. She should be the only pet in the household. Roxy is a wonderful, senior lady who deserves so much love and will return it immensely. She is just so sweet to have around you. Please consider adopting Roxy.

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
We cover Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Missouri, Nebraska, Oklahoma and Wisconsin and transportation is available for adoptions within those states. Stitch is currently located in KS.
Stitch is a very loving and sweet dog when you get to know him. When he first came to me he had major trust issues and we dealt with some resource guarding as well. He also has some food allergies. His food and his anxiety has calmed way down and now all of his fur has grown back in. Over the past two months Stitch has turned into a totally different dog, he is so sweet and wants to just sit down and cuddle. He is very driven by positive reinforcement and he really does try to please. One thing to note is Stitch is very energetic and will run circles through the house if you let him, he takes a stern and confident leader to guide and direct him. He is responsive to training and I will make him sit before I pet him and before I open the doors to let him in or out. He just needs a routine, I want him to go to someone who is able to work with him, you will need to be patient and confident in yourself with a large dog. I've introduced Stitch to a few friends who are over frequently and he is very friendly he just likes to jump, he just needs redirected to sit and he will calm down. I would take introductions to new people slow with him until he is familiar with them. Stitch has been around a smaller cocker spaniel a few time without any issues but I wouldn't trust him unsupervised with any dog. Stitch and my intact male intact Rottweiler don't get along that well do to dominance issues. Stitch would be better off with a single family preferably with no kids or animals and plenty of room to run. Also all gates must have a keeper because he's very smart and knows how to open gates lol.

animal.description:
Rowan, Rowan, Rowan on the river! The river of love that is! If you didn’t catch it, my name is Rowan! I am a beautiful, 5 year old, 40lb Shepherd mix! I am a pretty energetic girl who loves to play, so a fenced in yard would be amazing; it needs to be a privacy fence though because I can jump those shorter chain-link fences. I can be vocal at times when I get really excited, so no apartment life for me. I am good with other dogs and cats, but would also do great as your one and only furry family member. I do well with kids, but I do love to give hugs, so I could knock over some of the tinier humans. I am a super smart girl, so I am already house and kennel trained. I am currently learning basic obedience commands and how to walk properly on a leash, but it shouldn't take me long since I am so smart. Let’s get started on our adventures together and you can join me, Rowan, down the river of love! 

I am currently enrolled in the Pups 4 Parole training program, learning all of the things I need to know to make me a great family member. I need someone willing to keep up my training so that I don't forget everything I am learning.


My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Name: Blaze 

Sex: Male

Color: Red & White

Eye Color: Brown Eyes

Birthday: 03/11/19 estimated

Weight: 64 lbs. 

Large Dog Friendly: Yes

Small Dog Friendly: Unknown 

Cat Friendly: No

Crate Trained: No, he dislikes being in a crate and wouldn't do well in a townhouse/apartment with shared walls. His ideal home would work from home or have short days away from the house. He currently is taking a medication to calm his anxiousness.

Housebroken: Yes

Energy Level: Very High

Reaction to New People: Friendly

Kid Friendly: Unknown but should not live with children under 16 as he likes to jump on people and can be very mouthy.

Training: Knows sit, shake, lay down, will come when called (most of the time). Working on wait and leave it.

Grooming Needs: Blaze has a standard husky coat which will require frequent brushing. We are working on trust right now, as he does not enjoy being brushed on the hind quarters.

Fence: He would do fine with a fenced yard or a tie-out.

Solo or Siblings: He would do well as an only dog or with siblings that are willing to put him in his place. An active/young dog would make a great match for him.

Hi I'm Blaze! I was found wandering the streets so no one really knows my background. One thing is for sure, I didn't have too many rules or boundaries in my past so I'm kind of a big puppy. But it's ok! I'm working with a trainer to curb my enthusiasm to a gentle roar. I also get to go to daycare a few times a week to keep up with my socialization. I have to be reminded now and again that other pups don't like it when I...er....umm...jump on them, but I'm a work in progress! But my brain and body run fast so I'm looking for a partner in crime that will work me both physically and mentally. If you have husky experience and love to bikejor, skijor, snowshoe, hike, run marathons, I would love to meet you! These things all sound excellent to me! With my busy husky brain I need a mental work out too- obedience work, puzzle games, hide and seek, fetch, maybe even agility-let's get creative together.
Since I'm still learning how to dog, I would prefer a home with older kids or no kids, as I'm a bit mouthy when I play. I do good with redirection and ignoring when I'm playing keep-away or having a husky tantrum. Beware-I'm a shoe stealer and I will prance around with my find hoping to engage you in a game of "Catch the Naughty Husky. 
So if you are looking for a fuzzy buddy and willing to put the work in to mold this big ol' puppy into something nice to have dinner with, I'm your boy! I would love to find an active, strong leader hooman that wants to show me the ropes and help me be the best boy I can be. Is it you? Smash that button below to apply to adopt me. I'm so excited to become your bestest friend.

Adoption Fee: $400

All dogs coming into Adopt a Husky Minnesota receive care tailored to their needs, including: Nose-to-tail exam with a partner veterinarian, Vaccinations (Rabies, Distemper, Bordetella), 4DX test to check for heartworm or tick exposure, Fecal Analysis, Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative, Spay/Neuter prior to adoption, Microchip, and are evaluated for temperament and trainability.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Male
Estimated Date of Birth: September 28, 2007
Size: 50 lbs
Location: Dacula, GA

RESCUING HERMAN

Herman was a stray that had been roaming in Paulding County for a while. He has some mobility issues and a large abscess. The pound is no place for a senior to rest their head. Lucky for Herman, one of our loving foster families stepped up for him and he got his freedom ride on September 23rd, 2020.

ABOUT HERMAN

Herman was inquisitive about his new surroundings, but has settled in quickly. He has some skin issues likely due to poor diet and living outdoors, but with some quality food and TLC, he will soon shine like a new penny. As an experienced gentleman, he has some mobility issues on his hind legs, but he is on joint supplements to help give him some strength. As such, he is also a very calm guy who enjoys sunbathing and sleeping in a comfy spot. You can walk into his room and he won't even move. He is a quiet soul who takes life slowly and has no complaints. He enjoys being petted and will freely give kisses to whomever lets him. Herman is being quarantined to monitor for signs of an upper respiratory infection, but will eventually get to enjoy the company of other dogs soon. In the mean time, he is catching up on his sleep, love, and enjoys being treated like a king in his golden years.

*Please check back for updates on this old man*

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Due to Covid 19 all visitors must have an approved application before visiting our facility. This dog is 8 to 9 years old, weighs 90 pounds and her adoption fee is $200.

Suri came to us in August of 2012. She was a happy dog that loved to have her ears scratched ; she was born in animal control in Del Rio, where she was rescued. For three years she went to adoptions, but no one selected her. She was our mascot who ran all over the property with her friends. She was our little thief. She used to take all our tools, other dogs toys and just about anything she could get her hands on. She would take them and put everything in a pile by her favorite tree. Never destroyed anything.

We were excited when she finally found a home after being with us for 3 years. She has been with a family until recently. Due to Covid 19 they could no longer afford to care for a senior dog. She was returned to the shelter extremely obese. We are working on trimming her down. She needs a family where she will get exercise and the proper amount of food.

Old man Cam and would love a cool house to crash in. He had been a garage dog for most of his life. He has been in a foster home for a few months and loves being inside with his human and foster siblings.  His foster dad says he loves to lay by your feet.
