animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi, my name is Teddy.

I am a sweet, goofy boy who likes to hang out and observe the world around me. I look like an old man, but I'm believed to be around 5 or 6 years old.

I'm on the larger size at around 90 lbs, so it's probably best I go to a home with no young children. I get the zoomies and because I'm partially blind I might knock the little ones over. I'm also scared of loud noises, so I probably wouldn't be happy with little kids since they tend to be loud at times. Another thing I don't like is cats. I do like to chase them, though! I'm fine with all dogs.

When you leave it's probably best I'm crated. I have an incredible sniffer and I'm smart, so I'll try to open food containers and steal snacks! And oooh do I love snacks! I'm a very food motivated boy, that's for sure. I also really enjoy scratches, naps and prancing around the back yard with my fur sister.

Speaking of outside. I'm mostly house trained, but I won't tell you when I need to go out..so I may have an accident here or there. My foster family has figured out a schedule for me, which works quite well, so I rarely have accidents.

I do have some medical needs, but they are managed with proper medication. My foster family doesn't know my back story, but it's thought that there may have been a head injury at one point. As a result, I am blind in one eye and occasionally have seizures. The seizure meds I am on right now appear to be working pretty well, though! The other medicine I need is eye drops. They help keep the pressure down, so I remain pain free. Sounds complicated, but don't worry, I take my meds like a champ, especially when mom takes a small piece of tortilla, adds a little peanut butter and creates a peanut butter taco! So delic!

I am also unfortunately heartworm positive. Given my seizure history, my rescue family thinks it will be best for me to be treated with the slow kill method. This method uses monthly heartworm prevention, which the rescue will provide, to kill the worms. It will take awhile to be completely worm free, but for my overall health and well-being it's likely the better option.

If you are interested in adopting me, please reach out to your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please fill out an adoption application on our website.

https://www.freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org

I am being fostered near Raleigh. 2/1/21 11:41 AM

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Molly (SC) is a female Labrador Retriever mix rescued in South Carolina. Our veterinary partner estimates that Molly is 1.5 years old at the time of intake in October 2020. Molly is good with people of all ages, other dogs and cats. This sweet girl was in horrific condition when we rescued her, but she has received the medical care she required for her painful skin infection and she is now ready to go! Molly is a bit unsure of what's going on in her life, and she needs to be showered with love and kisses and be shown that life can be good.
Molly is a bashful, easy dog who looks to her foster family for reassurance on how to be a dog. She loves to snuggle and she loves cheese, peanut butter and vanilla wafers! Molly is very responsive to treats and rewards. She is house, leash, and crate trained. Molly's safe place is her crate and she insists that other dogs respect her place. Molly is stressed by loud noises and cars and must be leashed at all times.
If you can give Molly the love and patience she needs to trust that her life can be happy, please apply online to adopt Molly (SC) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

animal.description:
This is our long-legged beauty, Bailey! He is needing a household with particular qualifications.
Please read his FULL BIOGRAPHY before submitting an application. Thanks!

Bailey is a handsome fellow. He loves to play and can be quite the goofball! A fenced yard would be best for him as he loves playing ball (loves soccer balls!) and running around. Bailey is currently working on his fear and alertness of strangers and will need a family that is committed and patient while he continues to learn how to react to strangers appropriately. He is very intelligent, food motivated and so very eager to learn! His new family will need to have experience with or a willing and interest to work with a trainer.t! He's an amazing dog that is looking for the right family to provide him the patience, understanding, dedication and love to help him overcome his fear of strangers and to continue the appropriate training he needs to do so. 
Due to his needs and playfulness, he will need a home without young children (ages 15 and up may be okay), no cats and no apartments please. He has a history of doing well romping around with other dogs so another dog companion may be okay pending a meet and greet.

Bailey is currently hanging out at the shelter while waiting for a foster home. See instructions below on how to send in an application to come meet him. 

To meet Bailey, send an application (found here) http://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/AnimalShelter/Dog%20Adoption%20Questionnaire_Fillable.pdf to animalcare@seattle.gov - thanks!

Ivory is a 1 year old Chorkie/chin/maltese mix. His adoption fee is $400. He weighs just over 10 pounds. 

Ivory is a live wire :) He has a ton of energy and wants to be involved in everything. He is always finding something to keep him entertained (even if it is not doggie approved) and loves to play with the other dogs. He is very skittish. He will need a fenced in backyard and a home without young kids. He would also prefer other dogs in the home. He likes dogs more than he likes people :) he will learn though. He has a big bark and is a great guard dog at 10 pounds...hehe.

His hair is like that of a chihuahua so he is not hypoallergenic. He also marks in the house. Now that he is fixed it should slow down some.

His brother is Ebony and they are an amazing pair if someone is looking to adopt 2 dogs.

animal.description: When Roy came to the shelter he was understandably pretty scared, he had just lost his family due to a housing issue, and he wasn't very trusting of all of the new people at the shelter. We watched Roy come out of his shell little by little, and pretty soon he had made friends with the staff and some volunteers. Roy's previous owners said that he loves playing with toys, both tennis balls and squeaky toys, and he loves car rides, playing in the water, running and laying on the couch. We have introduced Roy into our playgroups and he is very playful with the right personality dog. He likes to play chase, but he gets a little scared if things get rough and rowdy. Roy seems to be housetrained and after some initial excited pulling, he walks well on the leash. Since he loves his people so much he can get a little stressed when they leave, so an ideal home would have someone home a lot, or someone who is willing to show him that it's not so terrible to be home alone. We are recommending that Roy go to an adult only home-even though he has been okay with children in the past, his fearful behavior is probably better suited to adults. We are pretty sure you will find Roy as charming as we do! Let's chat and see if Roy is right for your home! Check out my photos/videos!

animal.description: I won't be able to hear you tell me how cute I am because I'm deaf but I will know by how much you kiss on my loveable squishy face.   I came all the way here from Texas looking for a recliner chair to steal, a couch works too,  and full disclosure I'm kind of a bed hog!   My friends at the shelter keep asking me why my head tilts so much but honestly I don't remember??  I may have had an old injury that caused that and my deafness but know one really knows, what I do know is that I think its one of my cutest attributes.  If you are my new family I will need some help with a few things, I am a very loyal friend and I prefer to be introduced to new people very slowly, I'd maybe even like to admire my new potential friends from a distance a few times before we hang out.   I just want to make sure they aren't going to hurt either one of us before I allow them access to kissable face!  I love a good brisk walk but sometimes I get a little worked out with all the change in my environment, remember I need patience because I can't hear anything so my first reaction is to, well react and I bark.   My foster Mom and I are working on that but you and I will need some practice to get in the groove.  My foster Mom giggles constantly at my goofy antics and she keeps telling me there is someone out there that will love my companionship and will give me the quiet lifestyle she knows I need and so much deserve!!

animal.description: Hank is currently in Georgia at a trainer and this is her report: Hank is improving daily. He really is a good boy. He has an interesting personality where he is very soft and unconfident at first in a new situation (ie, new foster home), but warms up within a few days and needs a firm (but loving and kind) handler that will remind him of the rules! A strong pack leader makes him feel safe! Although he is initially very excited when he gets out of the kennel (we are working on not rushing through doorways!) he does know how to heel, sit, down, stay, come... but needs to be reminded, especially the first few minutes he is out. If he thinks he can get away with something (i.e. pulling on the leash) he will! He can be quite strong when excited - or if he spooks - and needs someone who is fit enough to not let him ever pull away and let him think that's an option! ) He is treat-motivated, and does take them politely. He tolerates some dogs, but will react to others. On leash, while we are working him, he is fairly easy to re-direct. He notices cats, chickens, horses, etc., but will avert eye-contact and not even look at them if told to leave it. (He is not at the point to get those same results off-leash yet!) He has a great coat, that stays amazingly shiny and clean - even after playing on the farm! No skin issues. He doesn't destroy blankets or toys, and keeps his denning area clean. I believe he did well with his housetraining at the previous foster home. He will be a very nice dog for someone willing to put in a little effort to establish rules and be consistent! Hank is approximately two years old. All information about the rescue and adoption can be found at ewenityfarmsbch.com.

animal.description: Panda girl!!  This sweet, sweet gal was found as a stray walking down the street with a gashing wound on her head.  Panda ended up at the county shelter with a lot of medical concerns.  When we were made aware of Panda, we went and removed her from the shelter.  Panda initially had issues with balance and her hind legs would slip from under her.  She also had an obviously head tilt to the right.  Panda had to have staples in her head to close the wound and she had a lot of smaller wounds throughout her body.  What happened to Panda?  How was she in this shape?  We will never know...what we do know is that she has had a lot of litters and her prior life was not the best.  She slept a lot and was a bit nervous around people.   After a slew of tests at the vet - both x-rays and neurological - we were relieved that Panda had no  obvious trauma to her body, meaning no broken bones or lingering head trauma.   What was assumed is her balance issues and head tilt was most likely from a severe inner ear infection.  For the last few months, Panda has been in a very stable, quiet and loving foster home and her daily progress is heartwarming.  She takes multiple walks a day and although she has a cute waddle, her endurance and balance is near perfect.   She jumps up on her foster dad's bed, she loves to sun herself outside and her daily walks have helped her become stronger.  We have not tested Panda with dogs as we have been focused on allowing her to get well and enjoy the attention of being pampered.  We think Panda is about five years old.  She will make a very loyal and grateful companion.  If you think you can give Panda her best life ($200 donation), please take a moment to fill out an application.  An application is a must and once received, we will contact you within 72 hours.  https://www.povertyspets.org/adoption-form.  Thank you.

She also must have a decent sized fenced in back yard because she loves to run and play! She cannot go to a home with young kids or super social teens as loud noises and new situations are scary for her. Her adopter must be patient and keep slowly working to build her confidence as her foster mama is doing. We know Lacey will be a wonderful family member with the right loving and patient family. She loves to cuddle and give kisses!

Lacey is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $250! As with all puppies adopted through Maxx & Me, her adopter will need to commit to continue working with a positive reinforcement trainer of their choice to help her continue to become a well mannered and confident girl.

To meet any of our dogs please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
In memory of Josephine Catanese
Grandma Great's Special Transport
A transport in memory of Josephine Catanese, better known as Gram. A special mother, grandmother, great-grandmother, sister, aunt, cousin, and friend. Gram's life centered around her family. She loved us, listened to us, taught us, encouraged us, advised us, and was always there for us. Gram had many pets through the years from fish and birds to cats and dogs. Most of which were acquired by her family and brought to her home where they stayed and never looked back. All of these animals weren't just animals, they became a part of her family. She even cared for the stray cats in her neighborhood, making a cat house with heating pads, plenty of canned and dry food, water, and medicine if needed. She exemplified love and kindness every day of her life. This transport in honor of our Gram is a continuation of her love and kindness of all animals.

Jess was born around October 15, 2016, and weighs about 25 pounds. Jess and 14 other dogs were surrendered to a southern high kill shelter when their elderly owner with dementia was taken to the hospital. Most of the dogs appear to be a Jack Russel Mix of some sort. A few of them may have some Border Collie mixed in and some have Basset Hound features. They arrived at the shelter covered in fleas and malnourished. These dogs are a touch shy at first but quickly melt into sweet cuddly wiggle butts! They are all thriving now and ready to find incredible homes where they will be cherished and adored. You may have some house training work to do as it's likely it didn't matter much where they went to the bathroom in their previous home but they will be worth the extra effort! Jess appears to be, perhaps, part Beagle. She is absolutely adorable and when she runs she....leaps with all four legs straight out in front and behind. It must be a breed trait, but haven't figured out what before, not sure I've ever seen a dog run like this - very athletic little thing! We will be looking for a home with another dog in it for Jess as she truly seeks out and is comforted by canine companions.

The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Ellie is a pretty 55 lb, 2 yr old Pitbull female. She has passed the cat test but would take a structured introduction to ensure everybody likes everybody. Miss Ellie is the sweetest girl despite her rough beginning to life. She is what we would consider a Velcro dog. Ellie would prefer to be next to her owner as much as possible! She is great with kids and cats, but dog selective. She would do best as the only dog in the home. Ellie is house broken as long as she is let outside after meals and drinks! Ellie walks great on a leash. She does not pull, but she may try to walk in front of you instead of next to you. Keeping her on a short leash to your side solves this issue. Ellie is a big snuggle bug especially after a nice walk! She will prefer sleeping with you at night! Ellies manners need to be fine-tuned. She does jump up on you wanting to be pet, but with persistence this habit can be broken. Ellie knows her name and has a great recall, except if there is a squirrel around! Overall, she is a beautiful, sweet, highly intelligent pup who simply wants and needs to be loved. 

The adoption fee is $300 and covers age appropriate vaccines, a microchip, and a spay/neuter.

 Applications are typically worked in time stamp order based on date/time of submission. If you have other dogs in your home, they must all meet the potential adoptee. It may save you a trip to bring them with you when you visit, if you are certain you want to adopt a new family member. 

*****We are currently operating by appointment only during the social distancing stage of quarantine. If you want to meet this pet, or are interested in adopting, please submit an inquiry or email to email@townandcountryhumanesociety.org.

Someone from the rescue will contact you and/or your family and determine, on a broad level, whether you might be a fit for the animal. If so, they will provide instructions for completing the application. Your application will be reviewed and you will be contacted to set up a time to meet at the shelter or the foster home. The introduction between you and the pet will be supervised by one of the dog counselors or the foster. If all goes well, you can adopt during the same visit.

Please be sure to follow us on Facebook to learn more about Town and Country Humane Society and our mission.

animal.description: Smile-y Malazan is looking for an extra special home. She is around 8 months old and we think she is a Lab mix. Her mama Fantasy is on the smaller side at only 30 lbs but we aren't sure what dad's mix is or how she will get. Malazan is an absolute love but needs a family who will help her build confidence in the world and also someone to set consistent boundaries. She needs slow but consistent introductions to everything new and then may need some downtime if she is feeling overwhelmed. She needs time to decompress in new households. She would do best in a home with no children or older children who would understand that she can need space. She is crate trained and mostly house trained but needs a routine. Malazan loves to play and wrestle with her foster dog brother but would do best with a well trained dog who tolerates little puppy teeth. She is leash trained but can be easily startled and is still working by on gaining confidence on leash. Malazan would do best in a home with dog experience (no first time dog owners) and with a confident dog to help show her the way. Malazan is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Malazan, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
NALA ~7 years old. Good with older considerate children, dogs, and cats.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only

Nala came into the rescue not because she wasn't loved, but because she was amazingly loved by the family she's known all her life. Rescue is hard because we see more heart-wrenching stories than the average person. I'm Nala's foster and took her directly from her wonderful family who made the hard decision to give her up because of a difficult circumstance they could not control. Most of the time rescue doesn't see the people behind the dog. With Nala, I did. I saw the love they had for her, I saw the tears they shed for her, I listened to the details about her personality they struggled to say because of the hard reality they faced of having her leave. Fostering has been the single commitment to find my dog a wonderful forever home, but in Nala's case, I am also being trusted by her family to find a forever home as wonderful as the one she came from. It's a responsibility I am taking very seriously.

Nala is a big sweetie who enjoys cuddling on the couch, eating, and having soft toys thrown for her retrieval. That's her softer side, on her naughty side, is nosing through bathroom trash and eating the paper products a trash can contains, and counter surfing. Maybe this eating obsession stems from the gut issue she is currently being treated for. We are working with our veterinarian to get her the proper diagnosis. Once thoroughly diagnosed, she will be available to go to her new home with instructions on how to keep her irritable gut happy and quiet. At the moment she is being fed a prescription diet and taking a few medications to manage it. I am still working with my vet to determine the cause of her symptoms, so it could be a short term issue or a lifelong issue that is managed. Nala also has an underactive thyroid that is remedied by a morning & evening thyroid replacement medication. It's not an expensive medicine, but one she will need everyday, twice a day, for the rest of her life. Her thyroid level will need to be monitored by a blood test by your veterinarian. Once medically cleared, she will need to be spayed; so adopting Nala isn't going to be quick, there is still work to be done to have her healthy & ready to be part of the family. A commitment GSRA stands by.

As for physical activity, Nala will take as many walks as you want to go on. She walks nicely on leash, but is easily distracted by a squirrel, so you'll want to have a secure collar & leash she can't run out of. Once the walking is done, she likes to sit in the backyard to watch birds & squirrels, and will be still as a statue doing it.

No doubt she is a fantastic riding companion. Anywhere you want to go, she's all in.

And when the day is coming to a close, she will want to share your couch. A good blanket and a pillow are the items she likes to ease her into the evening. And when you are ready to share the couch, she will politely scoot over to make room. As for her bedtime, she likes a bed of her own, but close by to you. She will sleep soundly all night, but is ready for the day the minute the alarm goes off.

animal.description:
Since TAGS is a smaller volunteer program, we are limited to facilitating adoptions only within Durham Region in Ontario. We encourage those applicants who apply out of area to check your local shelters and rescue programs. We are always happy to refer you to a program in your area.

Ginger is an approximate one year old beagle-basset-hound mix, and weighs just over 30 lbs.  She is exceptionally lovable, high energy and very playful.  After a day of walks and play, she loves nothing more than to cuddle.  She sleeps quietly in her crate with her fosters in the same room.

Ginger walks well on a gentle leader (halti) and is obedient to basic on-leash commands.  She walks well to heel but likes nothing more than to be at the end of her six-foot leash, on command, when she can follow scents.  She is definitely a ‘sniffing’ dog and when allowed a loose leash, walks with her nose to the ground.  She will be very happy with an active family who enjoy outdoor activities.  She loves walks, running unleashed and playing ball.  She does not appear to be apprehensive of water and in fact may be a ‘swimmer’.  

She enjoys spending time with her fosters’ young grandchildren (under 10).  Ginger should ideally go to a home with no cats.  While not aggressive, she is overly playful and wants to play ‘chase’.

Ginger needs ongoing socialization with other dogs.  There is no aggression, and she enjoys meeting dogs on her walks, it’s just that her enthusiasm with other dogs off-leash can be overwhelming. 

In her fosters’ home, she continues to have basic commands reinforced and is eager to obey.  It will be important for this to continue in her new home.  Because of the lack of stability and consistency Ginger has experienced in her short life she suffers from separation anxiety, which is why a home where someone works from home or is typically home during the day would be ideal.  However, this has been improving with the help of her fosters, and Ginger has all the qualities to become a wonderful furry family member.  What she needs is a forever home so she may establish security and feel loved.

Chico Cay is a 7 Month pup and is 27lbs and arrived here in Florida from BVI the night of July 4th. He is a firework and a wonderful active pup! He is Shy and Independent. He likes to watch from a distance before he gets involved (but who does not) and is crate and house trained. He knows some basic commands and loves to go on walks! He loves to give kisses and hugs on his own terms. Chico Cay loves treats and chew toys. He does take his time to eat his food but that is ok, he is being sure he can digest properly-LOL. He is a brave boy who is growing out of his shell daily and learning about the new world around him. He has gotten comfortable in his foster home with his foster dog siblings and even comfortable at the neighbor's house and their pets which he visits often. As with all puppies he needs guidance and training to learn the world and proper manners. He would benefit from a puppy training class, just like all kids he needs school and socialization. Chico Cay would love a home with a fenced in yard so he can run and play. Chico Cay wishes for a furever home of his own with a family preferably with mid-teen or older kids as he is still learning his puppy manners and no condo's as he loves his yard play time. He would be great in a home with dogs already or as a single dog with training. Come and meet Chico Cay today! He will re-pay you with a lifetime of love and snuggles!
DOB: 3/01/2020 Adoption fee for this pup is $175 and includes DHPP vaccination heartworm testing spay/neuter surgery wellness vet visit one month pet insurance deworming and microchip. All animals are examined by a veterinarian. Please fill out our application at https://gkarma.wufoo.com/forms/good-karma-pet-rescue-dog-adoption-screening/ if you would like to adopt or meet this puppy and we will be in touch right away!

Blanqui is a 3 y old female Retriever Mix, who came to us from the island of Puerto Rico as a stray rescue. Puerto Rico is experiencing an animal welfare crisis which was compounded by Hurricane Maria and the continuous earthquakes experienced in the southern part of the island. She is current on shots, spayed, and microchipped. She relates well with other dogs but is initially shy with humans. Blanqui is afraid of thunderstorms. She enjoys playing with other dogs with whom she is familiar. Blanqui weighs 24 pounds.

As with all of our rescues, we require a fenced-in yard, and a home visit prior to adoption. A fenced-in-yard is required, no exception. On the day of the agreed-upon date for the home visit, we will bring Blanqui with us. We will be wearing a mask and hand gloves to protect you as well as ourselves. The meeting will take place in your backyard. We only accept two applications per dog. We evaluate both applicants prior to determining who in our opinion is the best fit. If interested please complete and submit the dog adoption application available on this site.

We always recommend a meet and greet with our dogs available for adoption. We are not able to assess dogs with cats since we are set up for dog intakes only. If you have cats, we advise a proper introduction while keeping the dog on leash in your home.
We are volunteer-based, so please be patient with our response time.

FOR RESCUES: Taylor County is rescue friendly! If you are a rescue, please contact our Rescue Coordinator, Diana, at deed1123@aol.com

DONATIONS: We are always in need of donations to help care for our dogs. We feed IAMS Adult Mini Chunks (green bag) and IAMS Smart Puppy. If you can assist financially, please mail a check payable to Taylor County Humane Society at PO Box 243, Grafton WV 26354 or visit our website to donate via PayPal. http://www.tchswv.com/donations/

animal.description: Benito is a 40 pound adult Shep Whippet mix from India. Benito is one of the countless dogs saved by Guardians of All Voiceless. He was found paralyzed in his hind end at the bottom of a deep ditch. He had been there for a month, with a few caring people dropping food to him. He was miraculously and lovingly rehabilitated by the Guardians, and then adopted by a family in SC. Then Guardians learned that he was living OUTDOORS 24×7×365 because he has issues with incontinence. Benito is sweet and hilarious and likes certain other dogs who are not scary to him. Dogs who are big or rambunctious could hurt him (as he is fragile). He does like to play with other gentle dogs. He loves bones and toys. He is essentially house trained, as he is NOT destructive and will potty outside as long as given the opportunity and schedule. He does need to have his bladder "expressed" (and I can show any potential adopter how simple this is), but he is able to control his defecating. If you might be the special person or family for Benito, please contact Bev at 804-248-3042 or TrampsRescue@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
My name is Chloe, I came to BFF Rescue from a HIGH KILL shelter in Southeast Texas. I was in bad shape, but after some good eats, some TLC and some vetting I am looking good.

I am spay, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and on monthly heartworm preventative. My adoption fee is $175. 

With all that said, I did test positive for heartworms. I have had my round of doxycycline before I started my monthly medication.  If my new family decides they want to run me thru the more aggressive treatment, we have a donor who will cover the cost of that. My new family will have to get me to my vetting appointments and see that I follow instructions while receiving treatment. 

The only thing deadly about heartworms is if nothing is done.

NOW HERE IS THE BIGGIE. I MUST BE.... NO EXCEPTIONS...BE THE ONLY PET!!...I do not like other dogs and am sure a cat would be worse.  I love people and children. The person in my photos with me is a young lady about 14 yrs old and I love her and everyone else of the human kind that I meet. So I guess you could say, I want to be the only one with the key to your heart.

There is an application process. This does not lock you in, it just gets the adoption process started. A home visit is required and BFF can get that done, location is not an issue.

REMEMBER WHEN ADOPTING A PET, IT CAN BE A 15++ YEAR COMMITMENT!! PLEASE ADOPT RESPONSIBLY!!!!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi my name is Viktor and my life started out a little rough but I'm learning how to be a dog, one day at a time and making leaps and bounds. I love walks and am great at not pulling on the leash, sometimes the squirrels excite me and I wanna go after them but respond well to the "leave it" command for most things. I do great with all people and just want snuggles and love from everyone. The closer I can snuggle the better. I definitely consider myself a lap dog. Sometimes I get too excited and jump up on people when they first come in, I'm learning that's not okay. My kennel has a lot of bad memories for me but my foster parents are showing me that it can be pretty nice, I eat two meals a day in there and I love to "kennel up" for some treats. I still get really anxious when my people aren't around. If I can't see them I'm worried they may be gone for good so I tend to whine until I can see them again. I do best when my fosters don't acknowledge my whining. I really love the smell of your people food and you better keep an eye on it or I'll try and nab it. My foster parents and working with me to learn things such as sit, lay down, stay, and leave it. I'm getting better everyday but if there's a lot of distractions around I tend not to listen as well. I love all humans but dogs, especially big or aggressive dogs still put me on high alert. My owner will need to learn how to handle me around other dogs and help me learn that they will protect me and I don't need to anymore. I'm fully potty trained and haven't had any accidents. I sleep at the foot of the bed at night on a bunch of blankets and pillows. I usually like to sleep in with my fosters until around 8 or 9. I'm not sure how I would do around cats but I may chase them like I do squirrels.

Adoption fee includes: Full veterinary exam, alter, prepaid microchip, dewormed, Rabies vaccine, DAPP vaccine, Bordetella vaccine, 4DX

, flea/tick and heartworm preventative while in rescue. Adoption fee: $250.00

Love, patience and a second chance is what every dog deserves. Meet "Apollo" the sweetest and bravest boy who has so much LOVE to give and wants to be cherished in a new forever home! 

Apollo is a young 35 lb dog who came from a bad situation in which not an ounce of love was shown to him! This boy has the biggest heart and is eager to please, but needs to be taught how to love again!

FOSTER HOME:

- Apollo has been working very hard to ease into new experiences and is still a little scared, but has come a very long way!

- Apollo has a kind, but slighty fearful nature. It took a while for his foster parents to pet him, but he is trying his hardest through rehabilitation! 

FOREVER HOME:

- Apollo needs a family that understands his needs and is willing to be very patient in teaching him how to be a loved dog! He is very smart and eager to learn/please, with enough patience Apollo could become the PAWFECT dog!

- Apollo does very well with other dogs and his foster family think he would do great with another dog who can teach him the ropes! 

- Apollo needs a family that will not give up on him and understands rehabilitation takes time! 

- Apollo would need to belong with a family that has a fenced-in-yard.

*Apollo is fixed and ready to be adopted! 

If you’d like more information or are interested in this sweet boy, please text 4-6 photo's of your interior/exterior home and yard (including fence if applicable) to  foster Lisa at 813-245-4235.

- - -

Please Note: Inquiries through Pet Finder may be slower to respond and the best form of communication/inquiry would be through text message at the number above. Thank you.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Addi, as in Sweet Adeline. After a couple of years on the run and a few weeks in rescue, I'm ready to be adopted. Here is my story:

I was abused by a group of men who are notoriously horrible to their deer dogs down around the Hot Springs area. One day when out hunting, I decided to make a break for it and I never went back. At the time, I felt it was a good idea ... wouldn't it be a better life if I could get away from that horrible existence? Well, for the next two years, I survived on my own, living in the woods and scrounging for food wherever I could find it. I also had no permanent shelter and just did the best I could, sleeping under sheds when the weather was cold or rainy and sleeping As luck would have it, this past October, I became pregnant and gave birth to a litter of little hound puppies. I was in such bad shape physically, basically starving, only one puppy survived. 

Then, a ray of sunshine came along. A kind man came to me and picked up my puppy. I was hopeful he would love her as much as I did. I was frightened for my baby, but there was nothing I could do. Later that day he came back with a big bowl of food for me, and the next day, more food, and the next day, even more food! Although I have always been afraid of humans thanks to the situation I was in from my birth, where I was treated like a piece of property, definitely not a pet, I began trusting him. He was kind, had food and spoke softly and gently to me. I wasn't sure if it was a good idea or not, but I gave in and let him catch me. He took me home and there was my baby! Safe and happy. (Her name is Abbi and she is up for adoption too!)

I, however, was a wreck. Besides being extremely thin, I had mastitis and had to get to the dogtor immediately. So my new friend loaded me up and off we went. I'm over that hurdle. My next hurdle was having surgery to make certain I can have no more babies! It is so heartbreaking to watch your babies, one by one, die because you cannot give them what they need. So, I was all for that plan! Now spayed, microchipped and given my rabies shot, I am completely vetted and I'm gaining weight and my energy is coming back.

The nice people I live with are working with me to help me trust again ... it's hard ... but I am going to do it! I want to live in a home with loving people. 

My perfect home would be one with one person or a couple. It needs to be a calm home. Another dog would be great as I could learn how to act more like a normal dog. At some point, I may be okay with kids, but at the present time, my caretakers believe that would not be a good idea and it would be frightening for me. In my foster home, I've learned house manners, crate training and leash trained. Once very fearful of riding in a car, now I happily hop right in! 

I am the perfect size, 40 pounds, and everyone tells me I'm beautiful. I must have soft toys at my new home. I love to gather them all around me and snuggle with them, pretending they are my babies. A fenced yard is necessary to keep me safe. 

I hope there is a home out there that will give me a chance. Maybe it's yours ...

To apply to adopt Addi, please click the link below. It will take you to our Adoption Application.

To make the best possible match for you and the pet, please click below to complete the Adoption Application. 

Once your application has been processed, we'll be in contact. 

We cannot schedule a meet and greet without a completed application. 

If you are viewing this page through PetFinder, Adopt-a-Pet, etc., please go to http://ootwrescue.org/adoption.html to fill out an application or review our Adoption Process.

All animals waiting for adoption are placed in foster homes. Before placing the animal in a furever home, JHS provides all necessary vet care, including but not limited to: shots, spaying, and neutering.

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Roxy! Here is her video in NC:

https://youtu.be/457HRTvfr1A

Roxy is 2 years old (approx. DOB 10-20-18), female, 57 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped. Roxy was surrendered to the shelter by her family (we believe she was found as a stray and they couldn't keep her). She seemed really sad, scared, and confused in the shelter. Don't worry Roxy; you are safe now! She knows Sit and takes treats gently. She tested well with other dogs and seems a little shy of men. She loves to get the zoomies in the yard! Stay tuned for more information as Roxy is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Roxy please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out her Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

Go to the website, click on the adoption application link, enter the information and hit submit. After the application is submitted a staff member will contact you within 48 hours. animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Tonya! Here is a video of her with her BFF Rachel (more to come):

https://youtu.be/cpKqn2dtsxU

Tonya is 2 years old (approx. DOB 6-17-18), female, 60 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped.

Tonya was found homeless after being dumped off in a rural heavily wooded area with her BFF Rachel. They were loaded with ticks and had porcupine quills around their mouth. they would do best in a home with a yard and outside of a City environment (no apartments please). She is being fostered in a more rural area with Rachel and has been doing very well. Tonya's ideal home is one that is active and experienced to help her with training; she is very smart. No cats as she does demonstrate a prey drive and a home without very young children would be ideal as she is very excitable and a larger dog. A secure fenced in yard would be ideal for her to run and play!

If you are interested in adopting Tonya please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out her Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Are you looking for two very special, bonded ladies of your very own? Well look no further! These ladies are the full package—athletic, smart, spry, fun-loving, obedient and still young enough to take on the world right by your side! 

Please meet Molly Flint and Laken Flint! They are Lab mixes weighing in at 45 lbs of total cuteness! They were owner surrendered from Texas because their owner was moving. They are very close, even though they are not litter mates. Laken is considered special needs due to a deformed spine, but as you can see, it does not prevent her from walking, running or enjoying life. Her tail always lays to one side and while she is housebroken, every now and then she has accidents because she doesn’t have excellent tone and doesn’t realize. These very special girls would be lost without each other, so bonding their adoption is very important. They love attention, cuddling on the couch and being your best friends. They love playing outside, going for walks and riding in the car. They also love to help you cook, if you will let them, and they can find every morsel that you drop. They are housebroken and crate trained, and ABSOLUTELY ADORE TOYS, especially those that squeak and crinkle. They have adorable personalities, especially once they get to know you and settle in. They would love a family of their very own where they can enjoy life, relax, play, spend the day at the beach or sit by a bonfire. Whatever the adventure, these are your girls!

If you are interested in these adorable girls, please get your apps in as fast as you can!

THE APPLICATION LINK CAN BE FOUND ON OUR PETFINDER PAGE UNDER THE PICTURE. 

ANIMAL INFORMATION:  
Name:  Laken Flint
Breed:  Lab mix
Gender:  Female         
Age:  1 1/2 years            
Weight: 40 lbs           
Spayed/Neutered: Yes                
Vaccines: Current                      
Heartworm:  Tested negative on 8/28/2020, currently on Heartgard
Microchipped: Yes

FOSTER EVALUATION AND RECOMMENDATION:
Dogs:  Yes, fostering with dogs of various sizes, breeds and genders
Cats:  Unknown
Other Small Animals:  Unknown
Children:  Yes, they have NOT been tested with infants or toddlers, so proper supervision and introductions would be required. 

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
We are a foster-based animal rescue and we thank you for your interest in one of our animals. Our animals are fostered in various locations in the a South and in New England. Our fosters and adoption coordinators are the backbone of what we do. Our fosters work tirelessly to integrate our rescue animals into their home, so that we can provide as much information to potential adopters as possible. In addition, our coordinators offer as much information regarding the medical and behavioral and personality characteristics as is known to our organization. Without them, and our extremely generous donors, we would not be able to save as many animals as we do every day. With each adoption, we operate a Pay It Forward program, whenever possible, to help other animals in our rescue and future animals in need. 

If you are interested in one of our animals, please complete an application. The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture. You may also find our application on our website at www.petmatchmakerrescue.com under the Adopt page. If they are listed on our website, their adoptions have not been finalized yet. That does not mean that we have not received several applications, already. Please complete an application if you are interested and we will keep you apprised of their current status. We are all volunteers who work full-time jobs and have animals of our own, so please be patient with us. We will get back with you as quickly as possible.  

If you are interested in fostering for our organization, please complete an application.  The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture.

Lobo is a 4 year old White Shepherd who came to us from Kern County Animal Services on October 10th. He was a dirty, skinny, scared mess but is coming around in positive ways daily.  Lobo will be ready for adoption in December.
Note from Lobo (12/23/20): Hi my name is handsome, just kidding. Its Lobo. Haha
I am the perfect package. I am smart and good looking. I like a lot of attention so I hope you like to snuggle and spend time outside with me. I like to keep my figure so I need a family who is active like me. I love to run like a goofball. I run like no-one is watching. I love training and hanging out with my training partner. I am a loyal dog and want someone who stand by my sides because I will always stand by their. I am dog friendly, even though I am big. I play gently with others. Some time I get anxious but what can I say. I know what I want. I can be a bit pushy at times but I am well mannered.

animal.description:
Precious was given to someone to rehome because when he bred her she only had one pup.  The person was unable to find a suitable home for her, so she entered our rescue program.  She is a 4 year old girl who is friendly and  sweet , a little shy at first. She is nervous around young children, so would do best in a quiet home with adults and older children.  Precious does shed, all "doodle" mixes are not nonshedders. We are not certain Precious is a doodle - she could be mixed with a sheepdog breed.  She would enjoy the companionship of another dog. She has not been tested with cats,  but due to her calm nature, would probably be fine with them. Precious does have allergies, which can result in itching, and ear infections.  She will need an adopter who can financially afford to provide medical care for her.   Precious loves human companionship, and getting attention. We do recommend crating her until she learns your schedule. We also recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Precious will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
To apply to adopt, please fill out an adoption application here:

http://littlebigdog.org/available-dogs/
This handsome smart personable friendly happy dog needs a home with no dogs, cats or children. Gus is 87% American Bulldog and 13% Boxer. He is a ten year old dog who was picked up stray and taken to the local shelter. He was rescued and has been living in our senior sanctuary. We learned that Gus has a brain injury and cranial nerve injury. He can't bark, use his tongue, open his mouth wide, and his third eyelid is permanently closed over his left eye. Gus has multiple mast cell tumors. The tumors are very small and do not require removal.

Gus is a wonderful companion, loves cuddling, car rides, tummy rubs and back scratches. He hugs with both front legs, gives his paw, and sits on command.

Gus weighs 106 pounds and drools when he is hungry. Eating is a real challenge for Gus but if you give him enough time and space, he gets it done. Gus does not like elevated feeders and will take his bowl out and place it on the floor.

Gus is an indoor dog. He has exquisite house manners. He is neutered, negative for all tick- and mosquito-borne illnesses, up-to-date on Rabies and vaccinations, and OH yeah, he sheds.

If you have a heart for seniors please consider fostering or adopting Gus.Adoption fees are $200 unless otherwise stated. animal.description:
Lyla is a 3 1/2-year old female German Shepherd/Belgian Malinois mix dog. Shes a very sweet girl, who is doing really well in foster care, but is now ready for her forever home. She is house trained and crate trained. She has not had many life experiences, which makes her a bit shy with new people. Her new person can help her discover our great big world to overcome her shyness! 

Lyla has rough and tumble fun with her foster brothers and she also loves toys and balls. She is full of energy, and would make a great running partner. We believe she would also excel at agility, or another doggie sport of her liking. Lyla completed a 4-week basic obedience program and did very well learning commands. 

Lyla has more of the Malinois traits, is somewhat of a dominant female, and is really smart. An adopter must commit to continuing her training, and offering her firm guidance and leadership, setting boundaries and behavior expectations based upon positive re-enforcement methods. This will keep Lyla physically and mentally challenged, and ensure she remains on the path of a well-behaved canine citizen.

An adult-only adopter who understands the Belgian Malinois temperament, and have experience in successfully raising this breed will only be considered. Due to her prey drive, an adoptive home must not have cats or small critters. While she does get along with non-invasive male dogs, we feel she would be best suited as an only dog.

Our sweet pup will make a great companion dog for whoever is lucky enough to adopt her. Are you ready to go and meet that big world with this beautiful dog at your side?

animal.description:
Hidey was pulled with her two teenage puppies from a shelter on the Kentucky West Virginia border. They entire family was scared and undersocialized, likely knowing neglect and possibly abuse before arriving at the shelter. We are guessing her to be a 5 year old fiest mix and is about 25 pounds. After coming into rescue, she immediately began to hide and play hard to get, hence her name HIDEy. You can tell that she wants to make the break through to trust her foster family, and she keeps following them around closely, but as soon as they stretch to pet her...off she darts, until their back is turned again. Hidey is completely crate trained with no accidents, but the trick with her is catching her to get her to go into her crate at night. This scared girl isn't an off the shelf pet, she is more of a project pet and needs someone with patience and empathy that can help her take that final leap into trust and become the loving pet that she wants to be. Despite her fear, she is not a fear biter, once cornered she will allow her person to pick her up, pet her or handle her.

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting this baby, please fill out an application. They currently are fixed, up to date on shots, wormings, preventatives and are microchipped. Adoption fee is $188 ($175 Adoption Fee + $13 Lifetime Registration Fee for Microchip), applications can be filled out at this link. https://www.petstablished.com/adoption_form/10167/generic .We cannot guarantee breed or size when full grown.

Due to our current situation, with more great applicants than we have available puppies and young adults, we are no longer accepting applications from people that are over 150 miles away. Exceptions will be made on dogs over the age of 3, special needs dogs and direct referrals from our volunteers.

animal.description:
Hi, Im Lucille! Ive had a rough go of it for awhile but am now remembering how to be a good family member. I'm a senior chow mix estimated to be between 10-14 years old.

Im aloof as chows tend to be. I take my treats very nicely after starring at you and barking in demand for them. I LOVE going out the front door for walks, but as Im an older girl, around my fosters court is quite far enough. Dont try to just put me outside in the back yard thinking that will do....I am very smart, I know the difference! I know to go potty outside. I don't like crates but I'm a perfect lady being left out in the house. I am not interested in steps. I dont care that the humans are upstairs or downstairs, Im happy to sleep at the bottom. I do not get on furniture and I dont want to sleep in your bed. Im not fond of car rides. Im not bad, I will just whine and make sure you know Im not thrilled. My foster brother is an old, grouchy Weimaraner. I have no problem getting along with him. Im not sure Id like a younger sibling but an older one like him or none at all would be just fine. My foster family has four older kids - I love them (I dont think Id care for younger ones though). 

I'd love to meet you if you think I'd be a good fit for your home. Apply today at rescuedohio.org so we can meet up. My adoption fee is $195.

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Madre and I was rescued from Puerto Rico along with my pups before my arrival at Big Dog Ranch & Rescue. I'm an enormously sweet and maternal dog, who along with raising my own 6 pups, I took in 2 other puppies who weren't even mine to raise. I am very friendly with people and dogs but I can be scared and timid. I'm a much older dog and tend to be shy in new situations, but I'm extremely lovable. The team here at the ranch think that there's a possibility that I may be partially blind, however, this would make me a great fit for a home that already has a cat or other small animals. Because of my timid nature, I would do best in a home with an experienced dog owner who can teach me how to do to dog things! I could absolutely be happy in an apartment, but I would have to be able to get more comfortable walking on leash, which is very scary for me right now. I'm not the type of dog that would be happy going out and having adventures in public with you but I absolutely want to snuggle up next to you on the couch. I would benefit from further training but I am potty-trained. Also keep in mind, I can be a bit of an escape artist as I learned how to open my crate here on the ranch. All in all, I'm a dog that could be a great fit for anyone looking for a loving companion, I just need a little bit more confidence in myself.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary. Vet references are required and prior to adoption a home inspection will be conducted.   

Transport options available. Adoption fee applies.

animal.description:
Matilda AKA Mattie
Gender: Female
Breed: lab/rott/shar-pei mix
Age: 1 yr
Weight: approx. 60lbs

Dog friendly: yes, Loves to play with other dogs.
Cat friendly: Yes
Kid friendly: Yes

Potty trained: Yes
Leash trained: Yes
Kennel trained: Yes

Energy level: Low/Medium

BIOGRAPHY: Matilda came to the rescue with her brother Mikey. She is a very sweet girl who loves to play. She loves kids and dogs of all kinds. Matilda struggles with new people and new environments and unfamiliar items.  Mattie loves to play with balls and especially enjoys squeaky balls.  Matilda likes snacks, and will sit for a snack.  She is crate and house trained and likes spending time with her buddies Silver and Remington.  She is becoming fond of her foster dad and no longer leaves the room when he gets up to move around.  

Behavioral issues: Mattie chews on things when she gets bored, she enjoys chewing on antlers.  Mattie dislikes going for car rides, she will need to be physically put into a vehicle.  Once in the vehicle Mattie will drool for the trip.  Mattie struggles with new people, especially men in her environment.  Mattie is leary of men walking in boots and stomping their feet in her environment.  

Medical issues: Mattie has bilateral hip dyplasia.  She is on daily joint supplements with her food.  

Adoption fee: $100.00

Location: Dodge City
Please apply to adopt at www.tinyurl.com/adopthaa

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

animal.description: This handsome buddy is Sarge! We pulled him from a shelter when his time was up. We're not sure why he was there in the first place, but we're happy to be the bridge to the new life he deserves! Sarge is a 7 yr old Lab mix. He weighs about 70 lbs, and is steadily gaining healthy weight. He is really sweet and loving, and bonds easily to any human he meets. Sarge loves to ride in cars and go for walks, so someone looking for an adventure buddy would be a great match for him! He is pretty quiet and relaxed, but does like regular activity so someone with a fenced yard where he can run and play would be ideal. Sarge is mostly blind but it seems he can see shadows and lights. He navigates his area pretty well and goes in and out of a doggie door with no issues. Due to his vision, it is best that he is not in a home with small children. He seems to do well with friendly dogs, but prefers a cat free home. Sarge is just such a gem, and we can't wait for you to meet him!! He is neutered, house trained and up to date on vaccines. Email us at lasthoperescuefl@gmail.com to adopt!

animal.description: Steve Martin might be the funniest dog at APA! He is a dream to hang out with - the perfect brindle blend of athlete and couch potato. If you want to fetch or tug or jog... so does he. If you want to binge watch comedy specials... so does he. Steve is a nice guy that doesn't love a surprise. He wants to see your friends coming, but once he does, he's quick to love them because this guy wants an audience. Steve's residual puppy energy shows up when he starts demanding the spotlight. He will count on you to keep him a safe distance from other dogs when you are out and about because they aren't his biggest fans. Ideally, Steve would love a big safe yard, a lifetime supply of tennis balls and squeaky toys, and people that can devote some time into teaching him how to be a better boy. He's ready to take the stage.

Please fill out an application to start the process to meet Max! Meet and greets will be held in Tarzana, CA

https://pawsitivetailstoremember.forms-db.com/view.php?id=17980

MAX is 5 yrs old, he weigh 10 lbs, and we think he is a Chihuahua/Doxie Mix with a beautiful golden and white coat. Max is a bit shy and does not like to be picked up from the front (under his arms) so you need to let him know you are picking him up….but once you have him, he loves to sit on your lap and to cuddle.  Max was surrendered to the shelter with 3 other Chihuahua mixes - we took 2 of the 4; Max and Molly and the other 2 were privately adopted. Max has the typical energy of a 5 yrs old dog, and he is absolutely adorable. Max will need an adopter who will look past his shyness and to take a chance on him. Another small and older dog in the home would be a good fit for Max.

Max Faxs:

•	House trained using a doggie door 
•	Leash trained and loves to walk
•	Max is small and can easily travel everywhere with his family!
•	Max is microchipped, current on vaccines and is neutered
•	Max just had a complete dental and blood panel done last week!
•	Cute as a button and so deserving of his own forever family

Max’s perfect home will have a yard, another older small dog and preferably with someone who works from home, is retired, or will not leave him alone for long hours of the day. 

Like most dogs, Max would love nothing more than a warm lap and a family to call his own.

animal.description:
TIMOTHY is an adorable, 1-year-old, 40-pound Hound mix.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.

animal.description: Shadow is looking for his forever home.  Special needs Shadow has had such a rough life. He came to Rescue Dogs Dream two months ago after he was left abandoned in a home and the owners told the realtor to just have him put to sleep. She couldn’t do that, so she contacted us and asked us to help. Shadow is improving daily in a loving foster home but really wants to find his forever family. He is Heartworm positive but we have already started his treatment and he will come with a 1-year supply of heartguard. When we first got him he had extensive hair loss from flea dermatitis but with healthy salmon food and medicated baths, he’s doing great. He also was having a lot of difficulty walking but we have adjusted his pain medications and he’s doing great (we will provide 6 months of pain medication.)  Shadow is 8 years old, weighs 55lbs, and is a total sweetheart, he loves to snuggle with his person, go on short walks and ride in the car. He is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on shots. He is potty trained and crate trained. Can someone be his guardian angel and give him a FOREVER HOME?  Shadow is located in Dunnellon FL. If you are interested in setting up a meet and greet to meet sweet Shadow, please go to our website at www.rescuedogsdream.com and fill out an application located under ( about us) or email us at rescuedogsdream@gmail.com, or private message us on Facebook at Rescue Dogs Dream, Inc.

animal.description:
Hey there everyone! My name is Nilly! Well, technically I am named Manila, but Nilly is such a happy go lucky nickname, it fits me perfectly! My foster mom says when she thinks of me, she thinks of the theme song to the Andy Griffith Show, the light-hearted whistle tune. I’ve never heard it, because I’m a lot younger than my foster mom, (she says she is showing her age by knowing that song). Well, anyway,it is a happy tune and she says it fits me!

I am 4.5 years old, and such a pretty girl, if I do say so myself. I lived with a really nice lady almost my whole life, and she loved me a lot. How do I know? Well, when I was born, I had a BIG handicap. The veterinarian said I was a ‘swimmer puppy’. The vet even said I should be put down. But the nice lady couldn’t bear that thought and took me home anyway, she saw my loving personality and my sunny disposition. After I was about a year old, I got my pins under me, and let me tell you I never looked back. I can do the zoomies in the yard just as good as any of them!! I don’t have any trouble negotiating things, but on occasion I get a little too hasty and bump into things. If you have a Ming vase in your house, you might want to put it up out of my reach….

I’m sure you are wondering why I am in rescue. My family moved from town out to a ranch, and that’s where it started. Well, I am ashamed to say my prey drive got the best of me one day. My family had a bum calf in a pen. I managed to squiggle through the fence and the pursuit was on. No, I didn’t do unfixable harm, but the family knew it better not happen again, so here I am. I can’t get out where I am at now, but I sure would like to see how fast those deer can run, bet I could catch them if I really tried. My foster mom wants you to know I must have secure fencing. Due to my hind legs not being as strong, I can’t jump or climb out but I will try to find a way to dig or squiggle through a weak spot if there is a temptation out there.

My foster mom thinks I would be best as an only dog, simply because I do have a weakness in my hind legs and tend to be protective of them and wouldn’t appreciate another dog rough-housing with me. Cats would not be good, unless you want to see if I can catch one, (just kidding). Children would need to be 8 and up in age, and respectful of me. I would not intentionally hurt one, but I could accidentally knock over a small child.

A few words from Nilly’s foster mom: She is a delight!!! Happy is an understatement. She is a special needs girl, but should live a long and wonderful life. An ideal home would be someone that is there all the time, she follows me around like a shadow. She has lived outside much of the second half of her life, but I think house-training would be quite easy. She is protective of me when my other dogs are around, therefore my thoughts she might do best as an only dog. She is spayed, chipped, and up to date on all vaccinations. As she ages, a lot of stairs in the household would not be good, and slippery floors either. But when it comes to being a loving dog, she can’t be topped!

animal.description:
Autumn is a 3 year old female Hairy Hairless Chinese Crested rescued from a breeder. When we first rescued her she could barely walk and use her back legs. She was taken to the vet right away for testing.
X-rays looked fine, blood work came back normal however she does have a grade 1 heart murmur. Other than that they said she just had severely underdeveloped muscles and is underweight. She’s on puppy food and getting lots of exercise.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Frankenstein “Frankie” is an 8 year old male Poodle rescued from a breeder. He’s a 4 lb bundle of sweetness. If you are looking for a lap dog and loyal companion, Frankie is your man. 

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.
